WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.260 align:middle line:90%


00:00:13.260 --> 00:00:14.560 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA GARR: Hello and welcome.

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:15.700 align:middle line:90%
I'm Lisa Garr.

00:00:15.700 --> 00:00:17.560 align:middle line:84%
Some of the greatest
challenges of our time

00:00:17.560 --> 00:00:21.310 align:middle line:84%
can be understood by looking at
our past social patterns that

00:00:21.310 --> 00:00:24.090 align:middle line:84%
got us into where we
are as a society today.

00:00:24.090 --> 00:00:28.990 align:middle line:84%
So by looking at our history we
can better change our future.

00:00:28.990 --> 00:00:31.060 align:middle line:84%
Joining me today
is Riane Eisler.

00:00:31.060 --> 00:00:34.100 align:middle line:90%
She is a pioneer, a futurist.

00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:37.760 align:middle line:84%
She is an expert in the
study of complex systems

00:00:37.760 --> 00:00:41.390 align:middle line:84%
and making them very simple
for us to understand.

00:00:41.390 --> 00:00:45.760 align:middle line:84%
She's been recognized as one
of the top 20 macrohistorians

00:00:45.760 --> 00:00:48.810 align:middle line:84%
in the world, and has
written about new systems

00:00:48.810 --> 00:00:52.320 align:middle line:84%
for change in her iconic books,
"The Real Wealth of Nations"

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:54.080 align:middle line:90%
and "The Chalice and the Blade."

00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:55.450 align:middle line:90%
Welcome to the show.

00:00:55.450 --> 00:00:57.160 align:middle line:84%
Thank you so much for
joining me, Riane.

00:00:57.160 --> 00:00:59.380 align:middle line:84%
>>RIANE EISLER: It's a great
pleasure to be with you, Lisa.

00:00:59.380 --> 00:01:01.160 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It is my honor
to have you here.

00:01:01.160 --> 00:01:03.160 align:middle line:84%
And I am so looking forward
to speaking with you

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:04.670 align:middle line:90%
on a female to female level.

00:01:04.670 --> 00:01:06.640 align:middle line:90%
I have so many questions.

00:01:06.640 --> 00:01:08.650 align:middle line:84%
But first, I want
you to share with us

00:01:08.650 --> 00:01:10.770 align:middle line:84%
a little bit about
your past and how

00:01:10.770 --> 00:01:13.830 align:middle line:84%
you have come to
understand your past

00:01:13.830 --> 00:01:16.760 align:middle line:84%
and pretty much how it propelled
you to creating as much

00:01:16.760 --> 00:01:18.490 align:middle line:90%
change as you have.

00:01:18.490 --> 00:01:20.970 align:middle line:84%
Tell me a little bit
about where you grew up.

00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:22.830 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, as
you know, in my work

00:01:22.830 --> 00:01:27.020 align:middle line:84%
I introduce two new
classifications for society--

00:01:27.020 --> 00:01:30.620 align:middle line:84%
what I call a domination system
and a partnership system.

00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:33.850 align:middle line:84%
And I was born in
Europe, in Vienna,

00:01:33.850 --> 00:01:37.680 align:middle line:84%
at a time of massive
regression to the domination

00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:39.660 align:middle line:84%
side of what's
really a continuum.

00:01:39.660 --> 00:01:41.150 align:middle line:90%
It's always a matter of degree.

00:01:41.150 --> 00:01:44.260 align:middle line:84%
It was the rise to
power of the Nazis,

00:01:44.260 --> 00:01:47.960 align:middle line:84%
first in Germany, and
then my native Austria.

00:01:47.960 --> 00:01:51.080 align:middle line:84%
So that from day to the
next, my parents and I,

00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:53.800 align:middle line:84%
we became hunted
with license to kill.

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:55.485 align:middle line:90%
And I was a very small child.

00:01:55.485 --> 00:01:56.860 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How old
were you when you

00:01:56.860 --> 00:01:58.570 align:middle line:84%
started to realize
what was happening?

00:01:58.570 --> 00:02:00.470 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, I
was six years old.

00:02:00.470 --> 00:02:01.550 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Six.

00:02:01.550 --> 00:02:06.300 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And it was Crystal
Night, which was so-called

00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:09.090 align:middle line:84%
because of all the
glass that was shattered

00:02:09.090 --> 00:02:12.670 align:middle line:84%
in Jewish homes and
businesses and synagogues,

00:02:12.670 --> 00:02:15.970 align:middle line:84%
when a gang of Gestapo
men broke into our home

00:02:15.970 --> 00:02:18.750 align:middle line:90%
and dragged my father away.

00:02:18.750 --> 00:02:23.785 align:middle line:84%
And I saw that night, of
course, cruelty, violence.

00:02:23.785 --> 00:02:25.360 align:middle line:84%
But I also saw
something else that

00:02:25.360 --> 00:02:27.850 align:middle line:90%
had a profound influence on me.

00:02:27.850 --> 00:02:31.300 align:middle line:84%
And it's what I today
call spiritual courage.

00:02:31.300 --> 00:02:32.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Today you call it that.

00:02:32.700 --> 00:02:34.600 align:middle line:84%
But back when you
were watching that,

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:37.750 align:middle line:84%
it's amazing how
impactful that would

00:02:37.750 --> 00:02:39.310 align:middle line:84%
have been to a
six-year-old child,

00:02:39.310 --> 00:02:41.510 align:middle line:84%
and where you've come
today, what you've

00:02:41.510 --> 00:02:45.780 align:middle line:84%
done by teaching so many people
about what you experienced

00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:47.540 align:middle line:84%
at that pivotal
moment in your life,

00:02:47.540 --> 00:02:50.590 align:middle line:84%
about the domination
versus the partnership.

00:02:50.590 --> 00:02:51.979 align:middle line:90%
Explain a little bit about that.

00:02:51.979 --> 00:02:53.520 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, let
me first tell you

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:55.930 align:middle line:84%
who exemplified
spiritual courage for me.

00:02:55.930 --> 00:02:57.760 align:middle line:90%
It was my mother.

00:02:57.760 --> 00:03:00.180 align:middle line:84%
And she recognized
one of the Gestapo men

00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:02.447 align:middle line:84%
as a young man who had worked
for the family business

00:03:02.447 --> 00:03:04.560 align:middle line:90%
as an errand boy.

00:03:04.560 --> 00:03:05.730 align:middle line:90%
And she got furious.

00:03:05.730 --> 00:03:09.100 align:middle line:84%
She said, how dare you
do this to this man who

00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:10.360 align:middle line:90%
has been so kind to you.

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:11.887 align:middle line:90%
I want him back.

00:03:11.887 --> 00:03:13.220 align:middle line:90%
Now, she could have been killed.

00:03:13.220 --> 00:03:16.540 align:middle line:84%
Many people were
killed that night.

00:03:16.540 --> 00:03:18.130 align:middle line:90%
But by a miracle, she wasn't.

00:03:18.130 --> 00:03:20.750 align:middle line:90%
And by a miracle, we escaped.

00:03:20.750 --> 00:03:23.310 align:middle line:84%
But you know, I call
it spiritual courage

00:03:23.310 --> 00:03:24.950 align:middle line:84%
because we think of
courage-- we talk

00:03:24.950 --> 00:03:28.260 align:middle line:84%
you know, it's courage to slay
the dragon, kill the enemy.

00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:31.270 align:middle line:84%
But spiritual courage
is what she displayed

00:03:31.270 --> 00:03:34.860 align:middle line:84%
to stand up against
injustice, out of love.

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:37.880 align:middle line:84%
And in many ways that's
what my work is about.

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:39.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:03:39.130 --> 00:03:41.870 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And it's really
to answer questions

00:03:41.870 --> 00:03:44.690 align:middle line:84%
that arose very
early for me about

00:03:44.690 --> 00:03:46.780 align:middle line:90%
does it have to be in this way?

00:03:46.780 --> 00:03:50.760 align:middle line:84%
When we have such a capacity
for caring, for empathy,

00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:53.150 align:middle line:84%
for love-- what I
saw in my mother--

00:03:53.150 --> 00:03:55.010 align:middle line:84%
why has there been
so much cruelty,

00:03:55.010 --> 00:03:57.610 align:middle line:90%
violence, destructiveness?

00:03:57.610 --> 00:03:58.110 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:03:58.110 --> 00:04:00.900 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It existed way
before that time period,

00:04:00.900 --> 00:04:02.910 align:middle line:90%
and it has existed since then.

00:04:02.910 --> 00:04:04.350 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: That's right.

00:04:04.350 --> 00:04:10.280 align:middle line:84%
So I eventually-- eventually
it was these questions about,

00:04:10.280 --> 00:04:13.240 align:middle line:84%
does it have to be this way
or is there an alternative,

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:15.320 align:middle line:84%
that led to my search
for an alternative.

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:20.070 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't find it by using
the conventional categories--

00:04:20.070 --> 00:04:22.820 align:middle line:84%
right, left,
religious, secular--

00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:23.752 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Education.

00:04:23.752 --> 00:04:25.210 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well,
Eastern or Western,

00:04:25.210 --> 00:04:27.090 align:middle line:84%
for that matter--
all the categories

00:04:27.090 --> 00:04:29.360 align:middle line:90%
that we're so used to.

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:33.000 align:middle line:84%
Because none of them describe,
really-- none of them

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:34.140 align:middle line:90%
answer that question.

00:04:34.140 --> 00:04:37.090 align:middle line:84%
You can have terrible
regimes on either side.

00:04:37.090 --> 00:04:40.500 align:middle line:84%
And so that my first book
"The Chalice and the Blade"

00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:42.870 align:middle line:84%
really drew from this
multidisciplinary,

00:04:42.870 --> 00:04:44.820 align:middle line:90%
cross-cultural research.

00:04:44.820 --> 00:04:47.400 align:middle line:84%
And then, as you know, I
wrote many other books--

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:48.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Many, yes.

00:04:48.310 --> 00:04:51.890 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --applying the
partnership and domination

00:04:51.890 --> 00:04:56.800 align:middle line:84%
lenses to various areas,
including, as you just said,

00:04:56.800 --> 00:04:57.560 align:middle line:90%
education.

00:04:57.560 --> 00:05:00.180 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, which is
a great place to start.

00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:02.555 align:middle line:84%
And there was an entire DVD
that you did, which is great.

00:05:02.555 --> 00:05:04.054 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
see clips of that

00:05:04.054 --> 00:05:05.550 align:middle line:84%
today, from
"Tomorrow's Children."

00:05:05.550 --> 00:05:11.210 align:middle line:84%
And it really exemplifies the
explanation between partnership

00:05:11.210 --> 00:05:12.484 align:middle line:90%
and, well, domination.

00:05:12.484 --> 00:05:14.400 align:middle line:84%
We're going to take at
that clip really quick,

00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:16.700 align:middle line:90%
so we could see it in the DVD.

00:05:16.700 --> 00:05:17.600 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:21.350 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: This distinction
between the partnership

00:05:21.350 --> 00:05:25.480 align:middle line:84%
and dominator models
comes out of my research

00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:29.880 align:middle line:84%
over three decades,
multi-disciplinary research

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:33.940 align:middle line:84%
looking at a large span of
our cultural evolution that

00:05:33.940 --> 00:05:38.840 align:middle line:84%
is reported, in part, in my book
"The Chalice and the Blade."

00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:42.180 align:middle line:84%
This research addresses
fundamental questions

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:47.290 align:middle line:84%
that many of us have asked,
questions that in my life

00:05:47.290 --> 00:05:50.520 align:middle line:84%
came out of my experiences
as a little girl

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:54.250 align:middle line:84%
in Nazi Austria,
questions such as do we

00:05:54.250 --> 00:05:57.970 align:middle line:84%
have to hunt and
persecute each other?

00:05:57.970 --> 00:06:03.280 align:middle line:84%
When we humans have such an
enormous capacity for caring,

00:06:03.280 --> 00:06:09.240 align:middle line:84%
for creativity, what is it
that has tilted us back?

00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:12.585 align:middle line:84%
Don't we have any
alternatives to this way

00:06:12.585 --> 00:06:17.650 align:middle line:84%
that is so often presented to
us as just the way things are?

00:06:17.650 --> 00:06:20.570 align:middle line:84%
Out of this research
the answer came, yes.

00:06:20.570 --> 00:06:23.110 align:middle line:90%
We do have alternatives.

00:06:23.110 --> 00:06:27.840 align:middle line:84%
But we cannot see these
alternatives unless we look

00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:33.100 align:middle line:84%
at human history
through a wider lens.

00:06:33.100 --> 00:06:37.090 align:middle line:84%
What we begin to see is that
societies-- whether they're

00:06:37.090 --> 00:06:41.450 align:middle line:84%
ancient or modern, Eastern
or Western-- that orient more

00:06:41.450 --> 00:06:46.470 align:middle line:84%
to the dominator model, we
see that the primary principle

00:06:46.470 --> 00:06:51.770 align:middle line:84%
for organizing relations is
ranking-- man over woman,

00:06:51.770 --> 00:06:56.880 align:middle line:84%
man over man, race over
race, nation over nation,

00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:58.570 align:middle line:90%
man over nature.

00:06:58.570 --> 00:07:02.130 align:middle line:84%
But as you move more towards
the partnership model,

00:07:02.130 --> 00:07:07.460 align:middle line:84%
you begin to see a different
governing principle: linking.

00:07:07.460 --> 00:07:09.670 align:middle line:90%
There are still hierarchies.

00:07:09.670 --> 00:07:13.170 align:middle line:84%
There are still very clear
lines of responsibility

00:07:13.170 --> 00:07:17.180 align:middle line:84%
and leadership, but leadership
is not based on the power

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:21.170 align:middle line:84%
to dominate, to control
through fear, through force.

00:07:21.170 --> 00:07:26.070 align:middle line:84%
It is not disempowering,
but empowering.

00:07:26.070 --> 00:07:29.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, and leadership
can be empowering.

00:07:29.240 --> 00:07:31.790 align:middle line:84%
But right now in our
education system,

00:07:31.790 --> 00:07:35.400 align:middle line:84%
it appears that it
is very challenged.

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:38.090 align:middle line:84%
And we've heard this
for a while now.

00:07:38.090 --> 00:07:40.130 align:middle line:84%
How do you think
that this is being

00:07:40.130 --> 00:07:43.060 align:middle line:84%
used, the domination
versus partnership model,

00:07:43.060 --> 00:07:44.150 align:middle line:90%
in education?

00:07:44.150 --> 00:07:47.430 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, the
so-called No Child

00:07:47.430 --> 00:07:50.940 align:middle line:84%
Left Behind has really been
a symptom of regression,

00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:53.240 align:middle line:90%
again, to the domination side.

00:07:53.240 --> 00:07:55.080 align:middle line:90%
Because what does it really do?

00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:57.810 align:middle line:90%
It ranks us again, doesn't it?

00:07:57.810 --> 00:07:59.080 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The testing, yes.

00:07:59.080 --> 00:08:01.060 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Yeah,
and it humiliates.

00:08:01.060 --> 00:08:04.860 align:middle line:84%
It humiliates teachers and
schools that don't perform.

00:08:04.860 --> 00:08:07.610 align:middle line:84%
Well, the truth of the
matter is that children

00:08:07.610 --> 00:08:10.000 align:middle line:90%
learn when they're engaged.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.340 align:middle line:84%
Children learn when
they're cared for.

00:08:12.340 --> 00:08:16.800 align:middle line:84%
Children learn when there
is that sense that there is

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:21.180 align:middle line:84%
somebody that they're
with-- a teacher, a parent--

00:08:21.180 --> 00:08:21.950 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: A partner.

00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:24.470 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --who
really respects them,

00:08:24.470 --> 00:08:27.850 align:middle line:84%
who treats them as a
partner, not as just somebody

00:08:27.850 --> 00:08:33.720 align:middle line:84%
to tell regurgitate, repeat to
me, what I've just taught you.

00:08:33.720 --> 00:08:36.200 align:middle line:84%
So I'm afraid that
a lot of this,

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:40.220 align:middle line:84%
under the guise of reform,
has actually been regression.

00:08:40.220 --> 00:08:41.100 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The opposite.

00:08:41.100 --> 00:08:42.370 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Absolutely.

00:08:42.370 --> 00:08:44.700 align:middle line:84%
Now, we know what
needs to be done.

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:47.270 align:middle line:84%
And my book,
"Tomorrow's Children,"

00:08:47.270 --> 00:08:54.049 align:middle line:84%
includes really proven
methods that we know work.

00:08:54.049 --> 00:08:55.840 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, and they're
very good methods.

00:08:55.840 --> 00:08:58.230 align:middle line:84%
And I was in school,
I went through that,

00:08:58.230 --> 00:08:59.690 align:middle line:84%
where I just had
to regurgitate it.

00:08:59.690 --> 00:09:01.210 align:middle line:90%
And we took the tests.

00:09:01.210 --> 00:09:02.880 align:middle line:90%
And we were scored on the tests.

00:09:02.880 --> 00:09:07.950 align:middle line:84%
And it was nothing that I
could relate to at a young age.

00:09:07.950 --> 00:09:11.250 align:middle line:84%
School for me was
not as easy as I

00:09:11.250 --> 00:09:12.669 align:middle line:90%
thought it was for other people.

00:09:12.669 --> 00:09:14.460 align:middle line:84%
But yet, the other
people were experiencing

00:09:14.460 --> 00:09:15.430 align:middle line:90%
the same thing I was.

00:09:15.430 --> 00:09:17.144 align:middle line:84%
Now I look at my
daughter, who's nine,

00:09:17.144 --> 00:09:18.810 align:middle line:84%
going through school
these days, and she

00:09:18.810 --> 00:09:22.220 align:middle line:84%
has teachers who
act as partners.

00:09:22.220 --> 00:09:25.080 align:middle line:84%
But they still then have
to take the testing.

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:26.850 align:middle line:84%
So there's kind of a
double message there.

00:09:26.850 --> 00:09:30.320 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, it's made
it very hard for teachers.

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:33.620 align:middle line:84%
Most teachers, if you
talk to them, they'll say,

00:09:33.620 --> 00:09:35.170 align:middle line:90%
this is a diversion.

00:09:35.170 --> 00:09:40.370 align:middle line:84%
Of course, we need to have some
standards, some evaluation.

00:09:40.370 --> 00:09:43.064 align:middle line:84%
But the evaluation
shouldn't be like grading

00:09:43.064 --> 00:09:45.230 align:middle line:84%
on the curve, where somebody
has to be on the bottom

00:09:45.230 --> 00:09:46.290 align:middle line:90%
and somebody's on top.

00:09:46.290 --> 00:09:48.590 align:middle line:90%
That's pure domination teaching.

00:09:48.590 --> 00:09:52.740 align:middle line:84%
It should be what kind of
progress is this child making?

00:09:52.740 --> 00:09:56.470 align:middle line:90%
How is this child talented?

00:09:56.470 --> 00:10:00.650 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it isn't so much in this
area, but maybe it's in art.

00:10:00.650 --> 00:10:05.952 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it's-- in other words,
educata means to elicit,

00:10:05.952 --> 00:10:08.320 align:middle line:90%
rather than to cram down.

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:09.400 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:11.227 align:middle line:84%
Everywhere that
we go, though, we

00:10:11.227 --> 00:10:14.020 align:middle line:84%
experience this domination
model-- in our government,

00:10:14.020 --> 00:10:17.380 align:middle line:84%
in our systems, wherever we go--
when you get in an airplane.

00:10:17.380 --> 00:10:22.370 align:middle line:84%
It's all top down philosophies,
everywhere you go.

00:10:22.370 --> 00:10:28.000 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well and yet,
we have moved, very much,

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.850 align:middle line:84%
from much more rigid
domination times to today.

00:10:32.850 --> 00:10:38.200 align:middle line:84%
What we have is a very uneasy
mix of partnership elements

00:10:38.200 --> 00:10:40.080 align:middle line:90%
and domination elements.

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:42.320 align:middle line:84%
And if you look at
modern history, which

00:10:42.320 --> 00:10:44.600 align:middle line:84%
I've done through my
work, you actually

00:10:44.600 --> 00:10:45.910 align:middle line:90%
see something very interesting.

00:10:45.910 --> 00:10:49.350 align:middle line:84%
You see that every single
progressive modern movement

00:10:49.350 --> 00:10:51.887 align:middle line:84%
has challenged a
tradition of domination.

00:10:51.887 --> 00:10:52.970 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, this is true.

00:10:52.970 --> 00:10:55.136 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Whether it was
the so-called rights of man

00:10:55.136 --> 00:10:58.640 align:middle line:84%
movement, or the women's
movement, or the abolitionists

00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:00.880 align:middle line:84%
and civil rights
movement-- these supposedly

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:02.456 align:middle line:90%
divinely ordained rankings.

00:11:02.456 --> 00:11:03.830 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Even the
Occupy movement.

00:11:03.830 --> 00:11:05.020 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Well, absolutely.

00:11:05.020 --> 00:11:08.100 align:middle line:84%
Or the environmental movement,
challenging the once hallowed

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:09.970 align:middle line:90%
conquest of nature.

00:11:09.970 --> 00:11:13.030 align:middle line:84%
So what we're really
talking about here

00:11:13.030 --> 00:11:16.070 align:middle line:84%
is understanding
what needs to change.

00:11:16.070 --> 00:11:18.520 align:middle line:84%
And that's what this
work has been about.

00:11:18.520 --> 00:11:22.560 align:middle line:84%
And as I said in the video
that you just showed,

00:11:22.560 --> 00:11:26.460 align:middle line:84%
we have to look at areas-- we
have to think outside the box.

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:29.830 align:middle line:84%
Because usually, when we're
talking about society,

00:11:29.830 --> 00:11:34.340 align:middle line:84%
we don't talk about how
women fair in society, even

00:11:34.340 --> 00:11:36.102 align:middle line:84%
though we're half
of the population.

00:11:36.102 --> 00:11:37.060 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: More than half.

00:11:37.060 --> 00:11:38.110 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: More than half.

00:11:38.110 --> 00:11:42.300 align:middle line:84%
We don't talk about how that
affects our system of values.

00:11:42.300 --> 00:11:45.330 align:middle line:84%
We don't talk about how
children are treated,

00:11:45.330 --> 00:11:50.910 align:middle line:84%
whether it is partnership
care giving or dominator

00:11:50.910 --> 00:11:52.180 align:middle line:90%
care giving.

00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:55.440 align:middle line:84%
We hear a lot about
respect, but in domination

00:11:55.440 --> 00:11:57.760 align:middle line:90%
systems, it's fear, isn't it?

00:11:57.760 --> 00:11:58.970 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, yes, yes.

00:11:58.970 --> 00:12:00.821 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Respect
has to go both ways.

00:12:00.821 --> 00:12:02.320 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I remember
there was a quote

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:04.650 align:middle line:84%
that I read that if
women ruled the world,

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:07.280 align:middle line:84%
they would never send
their sons to war.

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:10.560 align:middle line:84%
Because no mama wants
to see her baby killed.

00:12:10.560 --> 00:12:15.150 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And yet, women have
been socialized, just like men,

00:12:15.150 --> 00:12:17.360 align:middle line:90%
to fit into domination systems.

00:12:17.360 --> 00:12:20.620 align:middle line:84%
In Iran, for example,
women actually

00:12:20.620 --> 00:12:24.350 align:middle line:84%
were asked to send their
children into the minefields

00:12:24.350 --> 00:12:27.100 align:middle line:84%
ahead of the army during
the war with Iraq.

00:12:27.100 --> 00:12:28.120 align:middle line:90%
And they did.

00:12:28.120 --> 00:12:30.640 align:middle line:84%
Because they were told
that their children would

00:12:30.640 --> 00:12:34.210 align:middle line:84%
immediately ascend
to heaven as martyrs.

00:12:34.210 --> 00:12:37.190 align:middle line:84%
So you have to really
consider that this is not

00:12:37.190 --> 00:12:40.440 align:middle line:84%
a question of anything
inherent in women or men.

00:12:40.440 --> 00:12:47.040 align:middle line:84%
It is really a question of what
kind of a system do we build.

00:12:47.040 --> 00:12:51.340 align:middle line:84%
And we have a lot
of evidence showing

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:54.590 align:middle line:84%
that partnership systems
have existed, do exist,

00:12:54.590 --> 00:12:55.860 align:middle line:90%
and that they work better.

00:12:55.860 --> 00:12:57.070 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And that
they thrive, yes.

00:12:57.070 --> 00:12:58.200 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: That they thrive.

00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:00.470 align:middle line:84%
But we have to bring
that information out.

00:13:00.470 --> 00:13:02.310 align:middle line:90%
Because it isn't.

00:13:02.310 --> 00:13:03.795 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, no
that's very true.

00:13:03.795 --> 00:13:06.170 align:middle line:84%
Especially-- I'm going to go
back to the education system

00:13:06.170 --> 00:13:07.586 align:middle line:84%
here for a minute,
because there's

00:13:07.586 --> 00:13:10.400 align:middle line:84%
another clip I wanted to show
about what Riane was talking

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:12.420 align:middle line:84%
about earlier, about
our education system

00:13:12.420 --> 00:13:16.320 align:middle line:84%
and how it is a conveyor
belt system of running kids

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:18.190 align:middle line:84%
through the mill of
an education system.

00:13:18.190 --> 00:13:21.040 align:middle line:90%
Take a look at this.

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:23.640 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: If you
look at the picture

00:13:23.640 --> 00:13:26.870 align:middle line:84%
that we get about schools
from the popular culture,

00:13:26.870 --> 00:13:31.165 align:middle line:84%
from television, where young
people, students, are moved

00:13:31.165 --> 00:13:36.590 align:middle line:84%
on a conveyor belt from class
to class, from grade to grade,

00:13:36.590 --> 00:13:41.000 align:middle line:84%
really like a factory, a place
where education is something

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:45.720 align:middle line:84%
that is done to students,
rather than with students.

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:49.735 align:middle line:84%
We all know that,
for real learning,

00:13:49.735 --> 00:13:54.271 align:middle line:84%
young people need to
be actively engaged.

00:13:54.271 --> 00:13:56.520 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, actively engaged
is very, very important.

00:13:56.520 --> 00:13:57.280 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Actively engaged.

00:13:57.280 --> 00:13:58.863 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So how does
this type of thing

00:13:58.863 --> 00:14:01.650 align:middle line:90%
address violence in schools?

00:14:01.650 --> 00:14:04.900 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, in
domination systems,

00:14:04.900 --> 00:14:08.210 align:middle line:84%
where you have this ranking,
people grow up with this notion

00:14:08.210 --> 00:14:09.920 align:middle line:84%
that there are only
two alternatives:

00:14:09.920 --> 00:14:12.550 align:middle line:84%
you either dominant
or you're dominated.

00:14:12.550 --> 00:14:16.630 align:middle line:84%
So war, the war of the sexes--
they're built into the system.

00:14:16.630 --> 00:14:20.210 align:middle line:84%
And violence is, of
course, the ultimate way

00:14:20.210 --> 00:14:22.350 align:middle line:84%
that domination systems
maintain themselves,

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:24.740 align:middle line:84%
whether it's in the
family, whether it's

00:14:24.740 --> 00:14:27.040 align:middle line:84%
in gender relations,
whether it's

00:14:27.040 --> 00:14:29.117 align:middle line:84%
in national or
international relations.

00:14:29.117 --> 00:14:29.700 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I see.

00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:32.540 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: So you can't
just tack on nonviolence

00:14:32.540 --> 00:14:34.610 align:middle line:84%
to a fundamentally
imbalanced system.

00:14:34.610 --> 00:14:37.350 align:middle line:84%
You have to understand
that we really

00:14:37.350 --> 00:14:40.830 align:middle line:90%
need really fundamental change.

00:14:40.830 --> 00:14:43.900 align:middle line:84%
And the movement today
against bullying,

00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:47.460 align:middle line:84%
for example-- that's a sign of
movement towards partnership.

00:14:47.460 --> 00:14:49.110 align:middle line:90%
Because it used to be accepted.

00:14:49.110 --> 00:14:51.770 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, there's a lot of
awareness being raised now.

00:14:51.770 --> 00:14:54.020 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Yes,
which is wonderful.

00:14:54.020 --> 00:14:57.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I just saw a
DVD on-- it was released

00:14:57.060 --> 00:15:00.470 align:middle line:84%
and it was shot by a
child, a nine-year-old.

00:15:00.470 --> 00:15:02.442 align:middle line:84%
And he showed, from
his experience,

00:15:02.442 --> 00:15:03.900 align:middle line:84%
of what it felt
like to be bullied.

00:15:03.900 --> 00:15:05.080 align:middle line:90%
And it went viral.

00:15:05.080 --> 00:15:08.276 align:middle line:84%
Very interesting-- so that
is how it's starting to work,

00:15:08.276 --> 00:15:09.900 align:middle line:84%
where the partnership
model is starting

00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:14.140 align:middle line:90%
to become a lot more supported.

00:15:14.140 --> 00:15:16.552 align:middle line:84%
And it has a lot to
do with awareness.

00:15:16.552 --> 00:15:18.260 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, there's
always awareness,

00:15:18.260 --> 00:15:20.890 align:middle line:84%
because from awareness
then flows action.

00:15:20.890 --> 00:15:24.240 align:middle line:84%
And the more changes we
make-- not only in ourselves,

00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:29.590 align:middle line:84%
OK, but in the cultural
structures, in the values,

00:15:29.590 --> 00:15:31.900 align:middle line:84%
in the relationships,
which are all

00:15:31.900 --> 00:15:35.640 align:middle line:84%
interconnected-- the more then
our awareness that something

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:39.010 align:middle line:90%
better is possible also comes.

00:15:39.010 --> 00:15:40.660 align:middle line:90%
So it's an interactive process.

00:15:40.660 --> 00:15:44.180 align:middle line:84%
I wrote a book called
"The Power of Partnership"

00:15:44.180 --> 00:15:46.560 align:middle line:90%
basically on that subject.

00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:48.910 align:middle line:90%
And it really is very useful.

00:15:48.910 --> 00:15:52.280 align:middle line:84%
I use it in-- I
teach leadership,

00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:54.290 align:middle line:90%
transformative leadership.

00:15:54.290 --> 00:15:55.195 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Thank God.

00:15:55.195 --> 00:15:57.420 align:middle line:90%
You teach leadership, yes.

00:15:57.420 --> 00:16:00.190 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And that's one
of the texts that we use.

00:16:00.190 --> 00:16:02.620 align:middle line:84%
Because it's so
very down to earth.

00:16:02.620 --> 00:16:07.370 align:middle line:84%
And it really deals with how we
relate to everything, including

00:16:07.370 --> 00:16:08.220 align:middle line:90%
ourselves.

00:16:08.220 --> 00:16:10.110 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We do actually
have another clip here

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:13.205 align:middle line:84%
of the violence in schools
and violence in education.

00:16:13.205 --> 00:16:15.269 align:middle line:84%
And it explains
the system of what

00:16:15.269 --> 00:16:16.560 align:middle line:90%
Riane is talking about in this.

00:16:16.560 --> 00:16:18.987 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:16:18.987 --> 00:16:20.570 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: If we
really think about it,

00:16:20.570 --> 00:16:24.770 align:middle line:84%
every curriculum is woven
around a particular conceptual

00:16:24.770 --> 00:16:28.010 align:middle line:84%
framework, around basic
assumptions, assumptions

00:16:28.010 --> 00:16:31.140 align:middle line:84%
that are then communicated
through the curriculum,

00:16:31.140 --> 00:16:37.100 align:middle line:84%
assumptions about what is valued
or not valued in a society.

00:16:37.100 --> 00:16:40.230 align:middle line:84%
Fortunately, we already
have quite a few partnership

00:16:40.230 --> 00:16:43.130 align:middle line:90%
elements in the curriculum.

00:16:43.130 --> 00:16:47.890 align:middle line:84%
But unfortunately, we
also have many elements

00:16:47.890 --> 00:16:50.830 align:middle line:84%
that we have inherited
from earlier times that

00:16:50.830 --> 00:16:53.480 align:middle line:84%
orient it more to
the dominator model.

00:16:53.480 --> 00:16:57.360 align:middle line:84%
For example, we tell
kids don't be violent.

00:16:57.360 --> 00:17:00.890 align:middle line:84%
But what are the dates that
we ask them to memorize?

00:17:00.890 --> 00:17:02.460 align:middle line:90%
The dates of wars.

00:17:02.460 --> 00:17:05.520 align:middle line:84%
So aren't we really
teaching young people

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:10.280 align:middle line:84%
that if you want to get into a
history book, go kill somebody?

00:17:10.280 --> 00:17:13.740 align:middle line:84%
Aren't we really
perpetuating the values

00:17:13.740 --> 00:17:16.599 align:middle line:84%
that we don't want
to perpetuate?

00:17:16.599 --> 00:17:19.500 align:middle line:84%
And the problem is that
this is so imbalanced,

00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:22.599 align:middle line:84%
because so little
attention in the curriculum

00:17:22.599 --> 00:17:27.579 align:middle line:84%
is given to nonviolently
achieved gains,

00:17:27.579 --> 00:17:30.560 align:middle line:84%
the social reforms
to which we owe just

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:32.940 align:middle line:84%
about all the good
things in our lives.

00:17:32.940 --> 00:17:38.070 align:middle line:84%
If we don't want young people
to be alienated and apathetic,

00:17:38.070 --> 00:17:42.700 align:middle line:84%
we need to show them that
nonviolent change is possible

00:17:42.700 --> 00:17:46.075 align:middle line:84%
and that they can
make it happen.

00:17:46.075 --> 00:17:47.870 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How do you
take a situation that

00:17:47.870 --> 00:17:52.430 align:middle line:84%
is as vast as bullying in
schools and really change it?

00:17:52.430 --> 00:17:57.090 align:middle line:84%
How do you make that real
social change happen?

00:17:57.090 --> 00:17:58.940 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, it
isn't just one thing

00:17:58.940 --> 00:18:01.470 align:middle line:90%
ever that makes for a change.

00:18:01.470 --> 00:18:03.720 align:middle line:84%
There's some excellent
programs, by the way,

00:18:03.720 --> 00:18:06.330 align:middle line:90%
now that schools are using.

00:18:06.330 --> 00:18:10.690 align:middle line:84%
My-- I have a number of
wonderful grandchildren,

00:18:10.690 --> 00:18:14.500 align:middle line:84%
and my 11-year-old grandchild--
he's a wonderful boy.

00:18:14.500 --> 00:18:18.920 align:middle line:84%
He is one of the people who is
in one of those in his school.

00:18:18.920 --> 00:18:19.969 align:middle line:90%
They have that program.

00:18:19.969 --> 00:18:21.010 align:middle line:90%
And it's a public school.

00:18:21.010 --> 00:18:24.740 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, public
schools are not failing.

00:18:24.740 --> 00:18:27.890 align:middle line:84%
There are just some public
schools that are failing.

00:18:27.890 --> 00:18:30.100 align:middle line:84%
And I have to say
that the charter

00:18:30.100 --> 00:18:33.000 align:middle line:84%
schools, on the surface, look
like they're doing better.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:35.649 align:middle line:84%
But that's because they
select whom to admit.

00:18:35.649 --> 00:18:36.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, that's true.

00:18:36.690 --> 00:18:39.220 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And so let's
not go in that direction.

00:18:39.220 --> 00:18:39.880 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK, OK.

00:18:39.880 --> 00:18:42.400 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: OK, but let
me get back to this--

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:46.372 align:middle line:84%
so the kids are learning that
bullying isn't acceptable.

00:18:46.372 --> 00:18:47.830 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Now, I
agree with you-- I'm

00:18:47.830 --> 00:18:49.820 align:middle line:84%
sorry to interrupt--
about the public schools,

00:18:49.820 --> 00:18:53.550 align:middle line:84%
is that it has actually caused
more emphasis on the parents

00:18:53.550 --> 00:18:56.880 align:middle line:84%
helping and participating
in their child's education,

00:18:56.880 --> 00:18:58.800 align:middle line:84%
because the government
support has been

00:18:58.800 --> 00:19:01.130 align:middle line:84%
so diminished, that
the parents really

00:19:01.130 --> 00:19:03.960 align:middle line:84%
have taken a larger
role in education.

00:19:03.960 --> 00:19:05.640 align:middle line:84%
They're assisting
in the classroom.

00:19:05.640 --> 00:19:07.740 align:middle line:84%
They're creating
parent-run organizations

00:19:07.740 --> 00:19:10.460 align:middle line:84%
that support the kids, with
the music programs and art.

00:19:10.460 --> 00:19:12.830 align:middle line:84%
It's really, actually,
been a nice backlash.

00:19:12.830 --> 00:19:15.830 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, the problem
is that this is all right.

00:19:15.830 --> 00:19:19.932 align:middle line:84%
And it's wonderful in the
sense for middle class

00:19:19.932 --> 00:19:21.640 align:middle line:84%
and upper middle class
families, but, you

00:19:21.640 --> 00:19:24.730 align:middle line:84%
know, lower middle
class families,

00:19:24.730 --> 00:19:27.890 align:middle line:84%
poor families-- they're
working two jobs.

00:19:27.890 --> 00:19:28.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: True.

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:33.180 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: They don't have
the time, the energy,

00:19:33.180 --> 00:19:34.310 align:middle line:90%
or the knowledge.

00:19:34.310 --> 00:19:38.090 align:middle line:84%
Because so many of
them have learned

00:19:38.090 --> 00:19:40.130 align:middle line:84%
parenting as you tell
your kid what to do

00:19:40.130 --> 00:19:41.630 align:middle line:90%
and you slap the kid.

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:44.810 align:middle line:84%
And of course, what are we
teaching a child if we do that?

00:19:44.810 --> 00:19:48.160 align:middle line:84%
We're teaching a child
that it's OK for somebody

00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:50.980 align:middle line:84%
to impose their will
through violence.

00:19:50.980 --> 00:19:51.840 align:middle line:90%
That's the lesson.

00:19:51.840 --> 00:19:52.881 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Domination again.

00:19:52.881 --> 00:19:54.390 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Domination, again.

00:19:54.390 --> 00:19:57.180 align:middle line:84%
So I think that what we
really have to look at

00:19:57.180 --> 00:20:01.590 align:middle line:84%
is not so much what the
individual parent does,

00:20:01.590 --> 00:20:05.830 align:middle line:84%
but what are the circumstances,
the social conditions.

00:20:05.830 --> 00:20:08.100 align:middle line:84%
And that's really where
we come to an area

00:20:08.100 --> 00:20:10.350 align:middle line:84%
that I'm working on
very, very much now,

00:20:10.350 --> 00:20:14.600 align:middle line:84%
which is social policy, and
especially economic policy.

00:20:14.600 --> 00:20:17.360 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: When you really get
into these individual systems,

00:20:17.360 --> 00:20:21.000 align:middle line:84%
where it's economics-- or
I mean, if it's education,

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:24.350 align:middle line:84%
or if it is economics,
or if it is social,

00:20:24.350 --> 00:20:27.340 align:middle line:84%
it's all interconnected,
as you're explaining here.

00:20:27.340 --> 00:20:28.340 align:middle line:90%
It's all interconnected.

00:20:28.340 --> 00:20:30.720 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Yeah, we're
taught such a fragmented

00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:35.230 align:middle line:84%
way of looking at things,
like religious or secular.

00:20:35.230 --> 00:20:37.740 align:middle line:90%
What kind of religion?

00:20:37.740 --> 00:20:40.840 align:middle line:90%
What kind of secularism?

00:20:40.840 --> 00:20:43.120 align:middle line:84%
Is it partnership or is
it domination oriented?

00:20:43.120 --> 00:20:44.860 align:middle line:90%
Or Eastern or Western?

00:20:44.860 --> 00:20:48.390 align:middle line:84%
A colleague of mine calls
these old categories weapons

00:20:48.390 --> 00:20:50.150 align:middle line:90%
of mass distraction.

00:20:50.150 --> 00:20:51.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Distraction, yes.

00:20:51.330 --> 00:20:52.310 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Because
they really are.

00:20:52.310 --> 00:20:53.806 align:middle line:90%
They fragment our consciousness.

00:20:53.806 --> 00:20:55.180 align:middle line:84%
And as you say,
our consciousness

00:20:55.180 --> 00:20:57.030 align:middle line:90%
is constantly fragmented.

00:20:57.030 --> 00:21:00.206 align:middle line:84%
And this approach is really
about connecting the dots.

00:21:00.206 --> 00:21:01.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I see,
that's what you've

00:21:01.580 --> 00:21:02.704 align:middle line:90%
done with all of your work.

00:21:02.704 --> 00:21:04.590 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Yes, that is
what my work is about.

00:21:04.590 --> 00:21:05.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, I could see that.

00:21:05.840 --> 00:21:07.940 align:middle line:84%
Between "The Real Wealth
of Nations" and then

00:21:07.940 --> 00:21:09.690 align:middle line:84%
"The Chalice and the
Blade" started it.

00:21:09.690 --> 00:21:11.890 align:middle line:84%
And "Real Wealth of Nations"
address the economy.

00:21:11.890 --> 00:21:14.670 align:middle line:84%
And then it goes into the
school system and the education,

00:21:14.670 --> 00:21:18.600 align:middle line:84%
with "Tomorrow's Children,"
and the partnership model.

00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:20.920 align:middle line:84%
I completely see how it
is all interconnected.

00:21:20.920 --> 00:21:23.350 align:middle line:90%
You're smiling because I-- yes.

00:21:23.350 --> 00:21:26.720 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, I'm
smiling because I realized,

00:21:26.720 --> 00:21:29.180 align:middle line:84%
down the road
someplace-- when I wrote

00:21:29.180 --> 00:21:32.140 align:middle line:84%
"The Chalice and the
Blade," it was about power.

00:21:32.140 --> 00:21:33.710 align:middle line:84%
Because the chalice
and the blade

00:21:33.710 --> 00:21:36.050 align:middle line:84%
symbolize two very
different kinds of power.

00:21:36.050 --> 00:21:37.800 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing
wrong with power.

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:39.970 align:middle line:84%
But is it going to be
the blade, the power

00:21:39.970 --> 00:21:41.030 align:middle line:90%
to dominate, to destroy?

00:21:41.030 --> 00:21:41.690 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Oh, I'm so
glad you said that.

00:21:41.690 --> 00:21:43.190 align:middle line:84%
Yes, that's a very
good distinction.

00:21:43.190 --> 00:21:45.940 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Or is it the power
of the chalice, the power

00:21:45.940 --> 00:21:50.060 align:middle line:84%
to give life, not to take it,
to nurture, to illuminate life.

00:21:50.060 --> 00:21:53.440 align:middle line:84%
And then the next book
I wrote was about sex--

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:54.854 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That came in there?

00:21:54.854 --> 00:21:55.770 align:middle line:90%
Oh, it came in, right.

00:21:55.770 --> 00:21:56.936 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: "Sacred Pleasure."

00:21:56.936 --> 00:22:01.100 align:middle line:84%
And then of course, the last one
is economics, which is money,

00:22:01.100 --> 00:22:05.540 align:middle line:84%
so it's really a trilogy
on power, sex, and money.

00:22:05.540 --> 00:22:07.150 align:middle line:90%
But it was funny.

00:22:07.150 --> 00:22:09.820 align:middle line:84%
I realized it after I wrote
"The Real Wealth of Nations."

00:22:09.820 --> 00:22:11.570 align:middle line:84%
I thought, well,
those are really

00:22:11.570 --> 00:22:13.510 align:middle line:84%
the most important
levers, aren't they?

00:22:13.510 --> 00:22:15.010 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, it's
absolutely true.

00:22:15.010 --> 00:22:17.160 align:middle line:84%
Because sex has
been used, as you--

00:22:17.160 --> 00:22:19.220 align:middle line:84%
I took this from your
book, "Sacred Pleasure"--

00:22:19.220 --> 00:22:26.310 align:middle line:84%
has been used to form humanity
in societies for decades,

00:22:26.310 --> 00:22:27.280 align:middle line:90%
centuries.

00:22:27.280 --> 00:22:31.950 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, the whole
idea that sex is bad

00:22:31.950 --> 00:22:35.800 align:middle line:84%
and that woman is a
temptress to man--

00:22:35.800 --> 00:22:42.010 align:middle line:84%
that absolutely-- look, if man
can't trust half of humanity--

00:22:42.010 --> 00:22:43.830 align:middle line:90%
everybody has a mother.

00:22:43.830 --> 00:22:46.710 align:middle line:84%
And if you can't even trust
that half of humanity,

00:22:46.710 --> 00:22:48.000 align:middle line:90%
you can't trust anybody.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.970 align:middle line:84%
And mistrust is
part of also what

00:22:50.970 --> 00:22:52.490 align:middle line:90%
keeps domination systems going.

00:22:52.490 --> 00:22:55.660 align:middle line:84%
But there's very good reason
to mistrust in those systems.

00:22:55.660 --> 00:22:56.864 align:middle line:90%
It isn't our imagination.

00:22:56.864 --> 00:22:58.030 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, right, right.

00:22:58.030 --> 00:22:59.080 align:middle line:90%
We've seen evidence.

00:22:59.080 --> 00:23:00.880 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Yeah,
it's the evidence.

00:23:00.880 --> 00:23:02.870 align:middle line:90%
So yeah, and education.

00:23:02.870 --> 00:23:05.960 align:middle line:84%
Always education, whether
it's formal education

00:23:05.960 --> 00:23:09.450 align:middle line:84%
or informal education
through the media.

00:23:09.450 --> 00:23:11.390 align:middle line:84%
We've got to pay a lot
of attention to that.

00:23:11.390 --> 00:23:13.110 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I wrote
"Tomorrow's Children."

00:23:13.110 --> 00:23:14.818 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And we're
going to touch on that,

00:23:14.818 --> 00:23:16.470 align:middle line:90%
which is very, very important.

00:23:16.470 --> 00:23:18.797 align:middle line:84%
Media, as you said, is
a form of education.

00:23:18.797 --> 00:23:19.380 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Yes.

00:23:19.380 --> 00:23:20.046 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It does.

00:23:20.046 --> 00:23:23.170 align:middle line:84%
It shapes and forms the
way that we-- our behaviors

00:23:23.170 --> 00:23:24.870 align:middle line:84%
as a society,
societal behaviors.

00:23:24.870 --> 00:23:27.300 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: But so are
fairy tales education.

00:23:27.300 --> 00:23:29.050 align:middle line:90%
So is religion education.

00:23:29.050 --> 00:23:34.240 align:middle line:84%
What does a girl take away
from stories like Cinderella--

00:23:34.240 --> 00:23:34.990 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Princess--

00:23:34.990 --> 00:23:36.281 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: --or Sleeping Beauty.

00:23:36.281 --> 00:23:37.300 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --rescuer.

00:23:37.300 --> 00:23:37.630 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: That's right.

00:23:37.630 --> 00:23:38.255 align:middle line:90%
She's helpless.

00:23:38.255 --> 00:23:39.360 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: She's a victim.

00:23:39.360 --> 00:23:41.260 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: She can't do anything.

00:23:41.260 --> 00:23:42.240 align:middle line:90%
It's ridiculous.

00:23:42.240 --> 00:23:42.765 align:middle line:90%
But also--

00:23:42.765 --> 00:23:43.640 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: She has to be saved.

00:23:43.640 --> 00:23:44.890 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: She has to be saved.

00:23:44.890 --> 00:23:47.390 align:middle line:84%
But not only that-- we are
still idealizing rankings.

00:23:47.390 --> 00:23:48.777 align:middle line:90%
Everybody's a king, a prince.

00:23:48.777 --> 00:23:49.860 align:middle line:90%
Those are the good people.

00:23:49.860 --> 00:23:50.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, yes.

00:23:50.740 --> 00:23:51.490 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: It's so subtle.

00:23:51.490 --> 00:23:51.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's true.

00:23:51.930 --> 00:23:53.304 align:middle line:84%
I didn't think
about it that way.

00:23:53.304 --> 00:23:54.750 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: It's so subtle.

00:23:54.750 --> 00:23:55.960 align:middle line:90%
And it's fascinating.

00:23:55.960 --> 00:23:59.340 align:middle line:84%
The work that I do is really
like a Sherlock Holmes

00:23:59.340 --> 00:23:59.840 align:middle line:90%
kind of--

00:23:59.840 --> 00:24:00.964 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You're a detective.

00:24:00.964 --> 00:24:02.460 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Yes, a detective.

00:24:02.460 --> 00:24:05.090 align:middle line:84%
Because a lot of things
that don't seem to make

00:24:05.090 --> 00:24:08.880 align:middle line:84%
sense suddenly
start making sense.

00:24:08.880 --> 00:24:11.610 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That everything is
based on this domination

00:24:11.610 --> 00:24:13.806 align:middle line:84%
versus partnership model,
everywhere you look.

00:24:13.806 --> 00:24:14.680 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Absolutely.

00:24:14.680 --> 00:24:16.470 align:middle line:90%
And we've inherited.

00:24:16.470 --> 00:24:18.260 align:middle line:84%
This is what we
have to remember.

00:24:18.260 --> 00:24:20.310 align:middle line:84%
If you look at the
European Middle Ages,

00:24:20.310 --> 00:24:22.425 align:middle line:84%
they looked like the
Taliban, didn't they--

00:24:22.425 --> 00:24:29.020 align:middle line:84%
the Inquisition, the Crusades,
the holy war, the jihad.

00:24:29.020 --> 00:24:32.870 align:middle line:84%
Women were nothing--
witch burnings,

00:24:32.870 --> 00:24:37.284 align:middle line:84%
whether you slowly stone a woman
to death or burn her to death.

00:24:37.284 --> 00:24:38.450 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: They're not leaders.

00:24:38.450 --> 00:24:39.574 align:middle line:90%
They were not leaders, yes.

00:24:39.574 --> 00:24:41.150 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: We have moved forward.

00:24:41.150 --> 00:24:43.390 align:middle line:84%
We have moved to the
partnership side,

00:24:43.390 --> 00:24:45.580 align:middle line:84%
but always against
enormous resistance

00:24:45.580 --> 00:24:47.200 align:middle line:90%
and periodic regression.

00:24:47.200 --> 00:24:50.640 align:middle line:84%
So it's like a spiral
upward movement with dips.

00:24:50.640 --> 00:24:52.570 align:middle line:90%
And we're in a dip now.

00:24:52.570 --> 00:24:55.600 align:middle line:84%
And I thought we would
be out of it already.

00:24:55.600 --> 00:24:56.750 align:middle line:90%
But we haven't been.

00:24:56.750 --> 00:24:57.680 align:middle line:90%
So it's up to us.

00:24:57.680 --> 00:24:58.920 align:middle line:90%
It's really up to us.

00:24:58.920 --> 00:25:01.930 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: In a
microcosm way, though,

00:25:01.930 --> 00:25:04.450 align:middle line:84%
don't we go from
the dips to the--

00:25:04.450 --> 00:25:06.640 align:middle line:84%
don't we constantly
spiral as a society?

00:25:06.640 --> 00:25:08.390 align:middle line:84%
Don't we go from the
hills to the valleys?

00:25:08.390 --> 00:25:09.510 align:middle line:90%
Don't we always do that?

00:25:09.510 --> 00:25:10.640 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: To some extent.

00:25:10.640 --> 00:25:14.310 align:middle line:84%
But I don't think that we
need to continue to do this.

00:25:14.310 --> 00:25:18.400 align:middle line:84%
I know that that's part
of Hindu philosophy,

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:20.840 align:middle line:90%
that there are these cycles.

00:25:20.840 --> 00:25:23.000 align:middle line:90%
I don't see history that way.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:25.930 align:middle line:84%
Because we started--
the original direction

00:25:25.930 --> 00:25:30.310 align:middle line:84%
of civilization, as I document
in "The Chalice and the Blade,"

00:25:30.310 --> 00:25:32.250 align:middle line:84%
was more in a
partnership direction.

00:25:32.250 --> 00:25:34.110 align:middle line:90%
And then came the shift.

00:25:34.110 --> 00:25:36.349 align:middle line:84%
And now, we're trying
to shift again--

00:25:36.349 --> 00:25:38.890 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well the shift was maybe
a bit of a backlash, though.

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:39.820 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: to the
partnership side.

00:25:39.820 --> 00:25:41.680 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Do you think that the
shift was a bit of a backlash?

00:25:41.680 --> 00:25:43.400 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well the
shift, I think--

00:25:43.400 --> 00:25:44.510 align:middle line:90%
there are many theories.

00:25:44.510 --> 00:25:48.400 align:middle line:84%
But I subscribe to the
climate change and invasions

00:25:48.400 --> 00:25:52.380 align:middle line:84%
theory, that in the more
fertile areas of the globe,

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:55.590 align:middle line:84%
where if you will, the Earth
was a good mother, the more

00:25:55.590 --> 00:25:58.600 align:middle line:84%
partnership-- never perfect,
never perfect, never ideal--

00:25:58.600 --> 00:26:04.280 align:middle line:84%
but less violent, more
egalitarian direction.

00:26:04.280 --> 00:26:07.900 align:middle line:84%
In the more fringe and
inhospitable areas,

00:26:07.900 --> 00:26:09.910 align:middle line:84%
you got more of the
domination system.

00:26:09.910 --> 00:26:13.090 align:middle line:84%
And during a period of
enormous climate change, which

00:26:13.090 --> 00:26:16.640 align:middle line:84%
has been aridification,
desertification-- you know,

00:26:16.640 --> 00:26:18.460 align:middle line:84%
the Sahara was
once very fertile.

00:26:18.460 --> 00:26:19.664 align:middle line:90%
Did you know that?

00:26:19.664 --> 00:26:20.580 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No, I did not.

00:26:20.580 --> 00:26:22.620 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Oh, we're not taught
the most interesting things

00:26:22.620 --> 00:26:23.700 align:middle line:90%
about our history.

00:26:23.700 --> 00:26:29.230 align:middle line:84%
But during this period, these
hoards began to encroach.

00:26:29.230 --> 00:26:32.960 align:middle line:84%
And there was this shift, even
in the more civilized areas.

00:26:32.960 --> 00:26:36.100 align:middle line:84%
So now of course-- and
also recorded history.

00:26:36.100 --> 00:26:39.940 align:middle line:84%
There has been, what you
said, this tension constantly

00:26:39.940 --> 00:26:44.190 align:middle line:84%
between these two-- in terms of
the language of chaos theory,

00:26:44.190 --> 00:26:46.370 align:middle line:84%
of nonlinear
dynamics-- attractors,

00:26:46.370 --> 00:26:49.570 align:middle line:84%
really, the partnership system
and the domination system.

00:26:49.570 --> 00:26:52.580 align:middle line:84%
But in modern
history, as I said,

00:26:52.580 --> 00:26:54.080 align:middle line:84%
all the progressive
modern movements

00:26:54.080 --> 00:26:56.340 align:middle line:84%
have challenged
traditions of domination.

00:26:56.340 --> 00:26:56.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:26:56.840 --> 00:26:59.090 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: So we have been
movement to the partnership

00:26:59.090 --> 00:27:02.180 align:middle line:90%
side with regressions.

00:27:02.180 --> 00:27:03.920 align:middle line:84%
So when I sometimes
joke about it,

00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:06.450 align:middle line:84%
I said, when I get depressed,
I think of the European Middle

00:27:06.450 --> 00:27:07.520 align:middle line:90%
Ages.

00:27:07.520 --> 00:27:09.547 align:middle line:90%
Because we have moved forward.

00:27:09.547 --> 00:27:10.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, we have.

00:27:10.740 --> 00:27:14.070 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: We would be killed
for this conversation just a few

00:27:14.070 --> 00:27:15.320 align:middle line:90%
hundred years ago.

00:27:15.320 --> 00:27:16.830 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You are
absolutely right.

00:27:16.830 --> 00:27:19.340 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: For even thinking
it, much less saying it.

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:22.360 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: On a public forum--
absolutely, you are right.

00:27:22.360 --> 00:27:24.060 align:middle line:90%
That is a great perspective.

00:27:24.060 --> 00:27:27.000 align:middle line:84%
Well, so what we need are
more models of how to be,

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:28.670 align:middle line:90%
more models of partnership.

00:27:28.670 --> 00:27:30.960 align:middle line:84%
We've definitely got the
model of the dominance.

00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:31.890 align:middle line:90%
So we see that.

00:27:31.890 --> 00:27:33.810 align:middle line:84%
And we see how we want
to move away from that.

00:27:33.810 --> 00:27:35.540 align:middle line:84%
But what we need
to see is models

00:27:35.540 --> 00:27:38.180 align:middle line:84%
of how to move towards
it, to visually

00:27:38.180 --> 00:27:41.770 align:middle line:84%
see that working in our
communities, in our schools,

00:27:41.770 --> 00:27:45.240 align:middle line:84%
in our societies, in our
economy-- absolutely.

00:27:45.240 --> 00:27:46.682 align:middle line:90%
That's what we need to see.

00:27:46.682 --> 00:27:48.140 align:middle line:84%
There's actually
a clip here, which

00:27:48.140 --> 00:27:50.540 align:middle line:84%
is a really good one,
about-- I love this.

00:27:50.540 --> 00:27:52.320 align:middle line:84%
This is back to the
education system,

00:27:52.320 --> 00:27:55.360 align:middle line:84%
on how children teach
what they learn,

00:27:55.360 --> 00:27:56.830 align:middle line:90%
right there in the classroom.

00:27:56.830 --> 00:27:59.262 align:middle line:90%
Take a look at this.

00:27:59.262 --> 00:28:01.220 align:middle line:84%
>>DAVE KETTER: I make it
a point, as a teacher,

00:28:01.220 --> 00:28:02.800 align:middle line:84%
to never do for
students what I think

00:28:02.800 --> 00:28:04.360 align:middle line:90%
they can do for themselves.

00:28:04.360 --> 00:28:07.100 align:middle line:84%
It's quite important for us,
as teachers, to get students

00:28:07.100 --> 00:28:09.800 align:middle line:84%
talking to each other,
and not just the teacher

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:12.330 align:middle line:84%
talking to the group or the
group talking to the teacher

00:28:12.330 --> 00:28:13.770 align:middle line:90%
and answering questions.

00:28:13.770 --> 00:28:16.606 align:middle line:84%
And pair teaching is a
major aspect of that.

00:28:16.606 --> 00:28:18.230 align:middle line:84%
>>JOSH BREWER: So in
the systems class,

00:28:18.230 --> 00:28:21.770 align:middle line:84%
specifically, we have
had this thing where

00:28:21.770 --> 00:28:24.590 align:middle line:84%
a student or a group of
students will take home

00:28:24.590 --> 00:28:26.900 align:middle line:84%
a packet or a
chapter or something

00:28:26.900 --> 00:28:28.400 align:middle line:84%
that they've
researched on their own

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:30.960 align:middle line:84%
and bring it back into the
class and present it and be

00:28:30.960 --> 00:28:34.260 align:middle line:84%
the teacher of that class
for 10 minutes or a day.

00:28:34.260 --> 00:28:37.000 align:middle line:90%
At some point we'll get to that.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:38.850 align:middle line:84%
I think that's really
helpful because you're

00:28:38.850 --> 00:28:41.060 align:middle line:84%
getting a different
viewpoint than you would--

00:28:41.060 --> 00:28:42.870 align:middle line:84%
you're not having
the same person

00:28:42.870 --> 00:28:45.580 align:middle line:90%
or two people present every day.

00:28:45.580 --> 00:28:47.700 align:middle line:84%
So hearing things from
a different voice,

00:28:47.700 --> 00:28:50.370 align:middle line:84%
from a different person,
with their influence in it,

00:28:50.370 --> 00:28:53.110 align:middle line:90%
it is really helpful.

00:28:53.110 --> 00:28:55.370 align:middle line:84%
>>MURIEL MONTGOMERY: I think
you'd learn more this way

00:28:55.370 --> 00:28:58.060 align:middle line:84%
because, instead of being
subjected to one point of view,

00:28:58.060 --> 00:29:00.160 align:middle line:84%
like the teacher talking
and you listening,

00:29:00.160 --> 00:29:01.915 align:middle line:84%
it's the teacher
bouncing off ideas

00:29:01.915 --> 00:29:04.865 align:middle line:84%
and the students bouncing off
ideas off of other students.

00:29:04.865 --> 00:29:07.710 align:middle line:84%
And so instead of hearing
one view, you get, like, 10.

00:29:07.710 --> 00:29:10.540 align:middle line:84%
Just socially, you get
interaction with other people

00:29:10.540 --> 00:29:13.390 align:middle line:84%
and, like, learn how to
politely receive ideas.

00:29:13.390 --> 00:29:17.892 align:middle line:84%
If I see somebody who's not
talking, maybe open their mouth

00:29:17.892 --> 00:29:19.350 align:middle line:84%
and act like they're
about to talk,

00:29:19.350 --> 00:29:22.990 align:middle line:84%
I don't say anything if
I've been saying things.

00:29:22.990 --> 00:29:25.880 align:middle line:84%
I see that a lot, just
courtesy in conversation.

00:29:25.880 --> 00:29:30.890 align:middle line:84%
People encourage other kids
who haven't spoken to speak.

00:29:30.890 --> 00:29:34.202 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's really
neat because in more

00:29:34.202 --> 00:29:35.910 align:middle line:84%
traditional classrooms
that I've been in,

00:29:35.910 --> 00:29:37.360 align:middle line:90%
that's not the case at all.

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:39.680 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's a great
example of a model

00:29:39.680 --> 00:29:42.340 align:middle line:84%
that-- where does that
school exist, by the way.

00:29:42.340 --> 00:29:43.130 align:middle line:90%
I looked it up.

00:29:43.130 --> 00:29:43.630 align:middle line:90%
I couldn't--

00:29:43.630 --> 00:29:44.713 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: The Nova School.

00:29:44.713 --> 00:29:46.490 align:middle line:90%
It was a so-called alternative.

00:29:46.490 --> 00:29:48.100 align:middle line:90%
And see, this is the problem.

00:29:48.100 --> 00:29:50.860 align:middle line:84%
All these models exist,
but they're marginalized.

00:29:50.860 --> 00:29:51.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:29:51.380 --> 00:29:53.700 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And our job
is to really bring them

00:29:53.700 --> 00:29:54.675 align:middle line:90%
into the mainstream.

00:29:54.675 --> 00:29:56.300 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I saw that
that was in Florida,

00:29:56.300 --> 00:29:56.960 align:middle line:90%
but I'd love to bring--

00:29:56.960 --> 00:29:57.835 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: No, no, no.

00:29:57.835 --> 00:30:00.830 align:middle line:84%
That school, actually--
there were a number

00:30:00.830 --> 00:30:04.800 align:middle line:84%
of schools in that DVD
of "Tomorrow's Children."

00:30:04.800 --> 00:30:07.700 align:middle line:90%
The high school is in Seattle.

00:30:07.700 --> 00:30:08.810 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, OK.

00:30:08.810 --> 00:30:09.487 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Yeah.

00:30:09.487 --> 00:30:10.070 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Great.

00:30:10.070 --> 00:30:11.360 align:middle line:90%
I was wondering.

00:30:11.360 --> 00:30:13.140 align:middle line:84%
That's an amazing,
amazing school.

00:30:13.140 --> 00:30:14.930 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Oh, it's
a wonderful school.

00:30:14.930 --> 00:30:17.630 align:middle line:90%
But see, the models exist.

00:30:17.630 --> 00:30:18.790 align:middle line:90%
And they work.

00:30:18.790 --> 00:30:21.550 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The curriculum exists
and it's even in your books.

00:30:21.550 --> 00:30:26.170 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And the point of
it is-- is to, as I said,

00:30:26.170 --> 00:30:28.620 align:middle line:90%
make this information known.

00:30:28.620 --> 00:30:30.297 align:middle line:90%
Change the conversation.

00:30:30.297 --> 00:30:31.880 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The curriculum
actually exists

00:30:31.880 --> 00:30:33.830 align:middle line:84%
with your organization,
doesn't it?

00:30:33.830 --> 00:30:36.920 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: We have a great
many resources at the Center

00:30:36.920 --> 00:30:42.680 align:middle line:84%
for Partnership Studies website,
which is partnershipway.org,

00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:46.480 align:middle line:84%
on all kinds of things,
and certainly on education.

00:30:46.480 --> 00:30:50.520 align:middle line:84%
So I really want to
invite our viewers

00:30:50.520 --> 00:30:53.190 align:middle line:84%
to avail themselves
of them and--

00:30:53.190 --> 00:30:55.650 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, and how
to raise young leaders

00:30:55.650 --> 00:30:56.780 align:middle line:90%
and young learners.

00:30:56.780 --> 00:31:00.200 align:middle line:84%
And yes, and how to really
change the education model.

00:31:00.200 --> 00:31:02.030 align:middle line:90%
It's being done.

00:31:02.030 --> 00:31:03.740 align:middle line:84%
And then you have--
your organization

00:31:03.740 --> 00:31:06.510 align:middle line:84%
has put together a wonderful
curriculum and resources

00:31:06.510 --> 00:31:08.890 align:middle line:84%
and so forth for it to be
able to be carried forth

00:31:08.890 --> 00:31:10.830 align:middle line:84%
to many different
school systems.

00:31:10.830 --> 00:31:13.422 align:middle line:84%
And I'm very, very
glad that you did that.

00:31:13.422 --> 00:31:19.870 align:middle line:84%
That is, in my view, putting
this conversation into action.

00:31:19.870 --> 00:31:21.470 align:middle line:90%
And it's making real change.

00:31:21.470 --> 00:31:24.360 align:middle line:84%
It's giving people practical
tools to make this to happen.

00:31:24.360 --> 00:31:28.220 align:middle line:84%
Because we as parents want
to see our children having

00:31:28.220 --> 00:31:30.350 align:middle line:84%
those options, getting
away from-- this

00:31:30.350 --> 00:31:32.290 align:middle line:84%
is the generation,
and the ones to come,

00:31:32.290 --> 00:31:34.580 align:middle line:84%
that change these
types of systems,

00:31:34.580 --> 00:31:37.130 align:middle line:84%
that move from the domination
to the partnership.

00:31:37.130 --> 00:31:39.820 align:middle line:84%
And that's how you do it, is by
putting those practical tools

00:31:39.820 --> 00:31:40.970 align:middle line:90%
into people's hands.

00:31:40.970 --> 00:31:42.080 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Yes.

00:31:42.080 --> 00:31:45.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And the
leadership organization

00:31:45.130 --> 00:31:47.630 align:middle line:84%
that you have as well-- I mean,
the curriculum that you have

00:31:47.630 --> 00:31:49.860 align:middle line:84%
as well-- tell me a
little bit about that.

00:31:49.860 --> 00:31:55.000 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, we have a
program for leadership training

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:59.110 align:middle line:84%
to really change
economic structures,

00:31:59.110 --> 00:32:01.870 align:middle line:84%
economic policies,
economic practices.

00:32:01.870 --> 00:32:03.930 align:middle line:90%
It's an online program.

00:32:03.930 --> 00:32:05.950 align:middle line:84%
You don't have to
leave your home,

00:32:05.950 --> 00:32:09.240 align:middle line:84%
don't have to leave
your chair, to take it.

00:32:09.240 --> 00:32:13.080 align:middle line:84%
And it's nine weeks, one
and a half hours a week.

00:32:13.080 --> 00:32:14.890 align:middle line:90%
And it's a fabulous program.

00:32:14.890 --> 00:32:19.670 align:middle line:84%
And I invite people to check
it out at partnershipway.org.

00:32:19.670 --> 00:32:22.112 align:middle line:84%
And you can find it when
you see those circles.

00:32:22.112 --> 00:32:23.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The circle of chairs.

00:32:23.320 --> 00:32:24.690 align:middle line:84%
Yes, and we're
going to be covering

00:32:24.690 --> 00:32:25.690 align:middle line:90%
that a little bit later.

00:32:25.690 --> 00:32:27.530 align:middle line:84%
But it's very
important to-- again,

00:32:27.530 --> 00:32:29.740 align:middle line:84%
to be able to put
these tools and to make

00:32:29.740 --> 00:32:31.090 align:middle line:90%
them practical for people.

00:32:31.090 --> 00:32:33.720 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: We also have a
wonderful caring and connected

00:32:33.720 --> 00:32:38.990 align:middle line:84%
parenting guide for the first
four years-- zero to four--

00:32:38.990 --> 00:32:39.740 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh really?

00:32:39.740 --> 00:32:41.614 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --based on
the latest neuroscience.

00:32:41.614 --> 00:32:42.950 align:middle line:90%
So you're quite right, Lisa.

00:32:42.950 --> 00:32:46.750 align:middle line:84%
There's a tremendous amount
of practical information

00:32:46.750 --> 00:32:49.010 align:middle line:90%
that can be used and adapted.

00:32:49.010 --> 00:32:50.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes,
absolutely, right away.

00:32:50.730 --> 00:32:53.770 align:middle line:84%
What is the-- just
curious-- the zero to four.

00:32:53.770 --> 00:32:55.690 align:middle line:84%
It really starts
there, doesn't it?

00:32:55.690 --> 00:32:57.730 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: It not
only starts there,

00:32:57.730 --> 00:33:01.030 align:middle line:84%
we know now from
neuroscience that those

00:33:01.030 --> 00:33:02.800 align:middle line:90%
are the most important years.

00:33:02.800 --> 00:33:08.560 align:middle line:84%
And that's why it's so shocking
that ours is the only developed

00:33:08.560 --> 00:33:14.110 align:middle line:84%
nation that does not offer
paid parental leave--

00:33:14.110 --> 00:33:16.400 align:middle line:84%
government supported--
that does not

00:33:16.400 --> 00:33:20.470 align:middle line:84%
offer high quality early
childhood education.

00:33:20.470 --> 00:33:23.220 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
really pay very dearly

00:33:23.220 --> 00:33:25.550 align:middle line:90%
if we don't change that course.

00:33:25.550 --> 00:33:30.490 align:middle line:84%
Because we cannot compete in
the post-industrial era without

00:33:30.490 --> 00:33:34.160 align:middle line:84%
investing in the capacity
development of our children.

00:33:34.160 --> 00:33:36.541 align:middle line:84%
And as we know, it
starts from zero to four.

00:33:36.541 --> 00:33:38.040 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So are you
saying that there

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:42.430 align:middle line:84%
needs to be an education
in place from zero to four?

00:33:42.430 --> 00:33:45.640 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: I think that what
we need are policies that--

00:33:45.640 --> 00:33:46.640 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Support parents.

00:33:46.640 --> 00:33:49.120 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Certainly, we
need parenting education.

00:33:49.120 --> 00:33:51.840 align:middle line:84%
Because what used to be
sound parenting education--

00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:55.490 align:middle line:84%
and that's still being peddled--
is dominator education.

00:33:55.490 --> 00:33:56.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It is.

00:33:56.840 --> 00:34:00.130 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Terrorizing a child
to accept that the parent's

00:34:00.130 --> 00:34:03.510 align:middle line:84%
will is law is perfect
for domination systems.

00:34:03.510 --> 00:34:05.932 align:middle line:84%
It's terrible for a
democracy, isn't it?

00:34:05.932 --> 00:34:06.890 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's very true.

00:34:06.890 --> 00:34:08.174 align:middle line:90%
And I agree with you.

00:34:08.174 --> 00:34:10.340 align:middle line:84%
But then, you still need
to be able to give children

00:34:10.340 --> 00:34:11.800 align:middle line:84%
boundaries, because that's
the most important--

00:34:11.800 --> 00:34:12.620 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Oh, absolutely.

00:34:12.620 --> 00:34:12.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And it's
not without that.

00:34:12.920 --> 00:34:14.378 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: I speak
of the difference

00:34:14.378 --> 00:34:19.679 align:middle line:84%
between authoritative and
authoritarian-- big difference.

00:34:19.679 --> 00:34:24.389 align:middle line:84%
And we need teachers,
we need parents,

00:34:24.389 --> 00:34:26.670 align:middle line:90%
we need loci of authority.

00:34:26.670 --> 00:34:28.170 align:middle line:84%
But the question,
again-- we're back

00:34:28.170 --> 00:34:30.290 align:middle line:90%
to "The Chalice and the Blade."

00:34:30.290 --> 00:34:34.360 align:middle line:84%
Is the power going to be
disempowering or empowering?

00:34:34.360 --> 00:34:36.650 align:middle line:84%
And the fact that in
the corporate literature

00:34:36.650 --> 00:34:40.600 align:middle line:84%
we now read about
empowering employees--

00:34:40.600 --> 00:34:43.239 align:middle line:84%
is very much, again,
another partnership trend.

00:34:43.239 --> 00:34:44.719 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes and that's--

00:34:44.719 --> 00:34:48.620 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: More rhetoric than
reality sometimes, but at least

00:34:48.620 --> 00:34:50.185 align:middle line:90%
we're changing the perception.

00:34:50.185 --> 00:34:51.560 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: In the
smaller companies,

00:34:51.560 --> 00:34:52.750 align:middle line:90%
it's definitely reality.

00:34:52.750 --> 00:34:55.790 align:middle line:84%
But yes, in the larger companies
it tends to just be on paper.

00:34:55.790 --> 00:34:58.050 align:middle line:84%
But that's very
interesting, though,

00:34:58.050 --> 00:35:00.950 align:middle line:84%
about the authoritarian
versus authority.

00:35:00.950 --> 00:35:03.880 align:middle line:84%
And that's a very, very
clear distinction there,

00:35:03.880 --> 00:35:05.710 align:middle line:84%
because it gives
children boundaries.

00:35:05.710 --> 00:35:07.820 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: They must
have boundaries.

00:35:07.820 --> 00:35:10.351 align:middle line:84%
Children-- they're
learning about--

00:35:10.351 --> 00:35:11.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Where they
fit in the world.

00:35:11.850 --> 00:35:14.391 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Where they fit in the
world, about what's dangerous

00:35:14.391 --> 00:35:17.540 align:middle line:90%
and what's good, what's bad.

00:35:17.540 --> 00:35:21.530 align:middle line:84%
That whole relativism that's so
fashionable in so many new age

00:35:21.530 --> 00:35:24.620 align:middle line:84%
circles about
don't be judgmental

00:35:24.620 --> 00:35:28.800 align:middle line:84%
is a straight line back into the
domination-- terrible, punitive

00:35:28.800 --> 00:35:30.170 align:middle line:90%
morality.

00:35:30.170 --> 00:35:32.110 align:middle line:90%
People need standards.

00:35:32.110 --> 00:35:34.620 align:middle line:84%
And if we say everything
goes, everything

00:35:34.620 --> 00:35:36.660 align:middle line:84%
is relative-- there's
a big difference

00:35:36.660 --> 00:35:39.810 align:middle line:84%
between understanding
why somebody bought

00:35:39.810 --> 00:35:42.420 align:middle line:84%
into-- like the women
in Iran I spoke about.

00:35:42.420 --> 00:35:46.880 align:middle line:84%
We can understand why they were
socialized to believe this,

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:49.850 align:middle line:84%
but that doesn't mean
that we agree with it.

00:35:49.850 --> 00:35:51.534 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What do you
mean by judgmental?

00:35:51.534 --> 00:35:52.950 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: By
judgemental I mean we

00:35:52.950 --> 00:35:55.420 align:middle line:84%
have to make a judgment
as to whether something

00:35:55.420 --> 00:35:56.450 align:middle line:90%
is right or wrong.

00:35:56.450 --> 00:35:57.580 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I see.

00:35:57.580 --> 00:36:00.120 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And I think it's wrong
to send your children ahead

00:36:00.120 --> 00:36:04.290 align:middle line:84%
of an army to explode the
mines, right, and to die.

00:36:04.290 --> 00:36:07.420 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you think the free
parenting thinking, where

00:36:07.420 --> 00:36:10.750 align:middle line:84%
parents raise their children
with more free philosophies,

00:36:10.750 --> 00:36:12.060 align:middle line:90%
is not necessarily healthy?

00:36:12.060 --> 00:36:14.100 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Not necessarily, no.

00:36:14.100 --> 00:36:15.950 align:middle line:84%
You see, what
happens so often is

00:36:15.950 --> 00:36:19.890 align:middle line:84%
you get rebellion rather
than reconstruction.

00:36:19.890 --> 00:36:22.510 align:middle line:84%
My work is about
deconstruction, certainly,

00:36:22.510 --> 00:36:25.760 align:middle line:84%
about understanding what
the problem really is.

00:36:25.760 --> 00:36:27.880 align:middle line:84%
But it's not about
rebelling against it,

00:36:27.880 --> 00:36:29.732 align:middle line:84%
which is what the
free parenting was.

00:36:29.732 --> 00:36:30.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The parents do.

00:36:30.690 --> 00:36:31.970 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: It's about
reconstructing.

00:36:31.970 --> 00:36:34.090 align:middle line:84%
And that's what the Caring
and Connected Parenting

00:36:34.090 --> 00:36:35.820 align:middle line:90%
Guide is about.

00:36:35.820 --> 00:36:41.060 align:middle line:84%
It is not about the child
becoming the dominator.

00:36:41.060 --> 00:36:42.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's very true.

00:36:42.440 --> 00:36:43.210 align:middle line:90%
That's very true.

00:36:43.210 --> 00:36:46.130 align:middle line:84%
And I-- yes, I can see how that
would make a big difference.

00:36:46.130 --> 00:36:48.790 align:middle line:84%
We've done both sides
of that parenting model.

00:36:48.790 --> 00:36:50.490 align:middle line:84%
And I see the one
with the boundaries

00:36:50.490 --> 00:36:52.070 align:middle line:90%
works so much better.

00:36:52.070 --> 00:36:56.490 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, because we
are really relearning so much.

00:36:56.490 --> 00:36:59.640 align:middle line:84%
And that's what-- but we
have to unlearn and learn

00:36:59.640 --> 00:37:00.510 align:middle line:90%
something new.

00:37:00.510 --> 00:37:02.446 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Such a beautiful
way of saying that.

00:37:02.446 --> 00:37:04.545 align:middle line:84%
You have a beautiful way
of say things, Riane.

00:37:04.545 --> 00:37:05.920 align:middle line:84%
All right, what
we're going to do

00:37:05.920 --> 00:37:07.230 align:middle line:84%
is we're going to
take a quick break.

00:37:07.230 --> 00:37:09.820 align:middle line:84%
When we come back, we're going
to talk more about the social

00:37:09.820 --> 00:37:12.210 align:middle line:84%
and the economical
perspectives of all this,

00:37:12.210 --> 00:37:14.910 align:middle line:84%
and how it goes into
a caring economy,

00:37:14.910 --> 00:37:17.187 align:middle line:84%
and how those two words
actually work together.

