You mentioned something in your
work called caring economics.

00:37:46.550 --> 00:37:47.880 align:middle line:90%
What exactly is that?

00:37:47.880 --> 00:37:49.644 align:middle line:90%
What is a caring economics?

00:37:49.644 --> 00:37:51.310 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Don't we
do a double take just

00:37:51.310 --> 00:37:53.640 align:middle line:84%
hearing caring and economics
in the same sentence?

00:37:53.640 --> 00:37:55.620 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's an
oxymoron, kind of.

00:37:55.620 --> 00:37:56.820 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: But should it be?

00:37:56.820 --> 00:37:58.585 align:middle line:84%
Isn't that a terrible
comment, Lisa--

00:37:58.585 --> 00:37:59.460 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I know, true.

00:37:59.460 --> 00:38:01.230 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: No, think
about it-- on how

00:38:01.230 --> 00:38:05.090 align:middle line:84%
we've been taught that
uncaring values should

00:38:05.090 --> 00:38:07.190 align:middle line:90%
drive our economic systems.

00:38:07.190 --> 00:38:10.960 align:middle line:84%
Economic systems are
supposed-- supposed to--

00:38:10.960 --> 00:38:11.900 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Support us.

00:38:11.900 --> 00:38:12.980 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: That's right.

00:38:12.980 --> 00:38:13.855 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You're right.

00:38:13.855 --> 00:38:14.540 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: So--

00:38:14.540 --> 00:38:16.900 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We have gone
so far away from that.

00:38:16.900 --> 00:38:18.890 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, and
there's a reason for that.

00:38:18.890 --> 00:38:22.300 align:middle line:84%
And it has to do with what
we've been talking about,

00:38:22.300 --> 00:38:25.360 align:middle line:84%
which is domination
or partnership.

00:38:25.360 --> 00:38:27.940 align:middle line:84%
Because economics don't
arise in a vacuum.

00:38:27.940 --> 00:38:30.130 align:middle line:90%
They arise in a context.

00:38:30.130 --> 00:38:33.440 align:middle line:84%
And we still have so
many domination elements.

00:38:33.440 --> 00:38:35.510 align:middle line:84%
And part of the
domination system,

00:38:35.510 --> 00:38:39.790 align:middle line:84%
if you remember from
that clip, is the ranking

00:38:39.790 --> 00:38:43.287 align:middle line:84%
of the male half of humanity
over the female half.

00:38:43.287 --> 00:38:44.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Historically, yes.

00:38:44.370 --> 00:38:46.530 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Historically.

00:38:46.530 --> 00:38:52.990 align:middle line:84%
And with this comes a very
gendered system of values,

00:38:52.990 --> 00:38:56.780 align:middle line:84%
where anything that's
stereotypically associated

00:38:56.780 --> 00:39:01.230 align:middle line:84%
with women or the feminine--
caring, care giving,

00:39:01.230 --> 00:39:04.760 align:middle line:84%
nonviolence-- is
devalued, whether it's

00:39:04.760 --> 00:39:06.170 align:middle line:90%
in a woman or a man.

00:39:06.170 --> 00:39:08.930 align:middle line:84%
If a man-- he's a sissy
in the old system, right?

00:39:08.930 --> 00:39:10.190 align:middle line:90%
He's a wimp.

00:39:10.190 --> 00:39:11.370 align:middle line:90%
He's effeminate.

00:39:11.370 --> 00:39:13.450 align:middle line:84%
Why should effeminate
be an insult?

00:39:13.450 --> 00:39:15.160 align:middle line:90%
But think about it.

00:39:15.160 --> 00:39:20.060 align:middle line:84%
And it's also devalued in our
economic and business policy.

00:39:20.060 --> 00:39:22.770 align:middle line:84%
Once we become aware
of this, again,

00:39:22.770 --> 00:39:27.640 align:middle line:84%
a lot of things that don't seem
to make any sense-- after all,

00:39:27.640 --> 00:39:32.320 align:middle line:84%
why shouldn't we
really support caring

00:39:32.320 --> 00:39:36.900 align:middle line:84%
for people and for
nature-- come into play.

00:39:36.900 --> 00:39:39.430 align:middle line:84%
It's because we've
been socialized

00:39:39.430 --> 00:39:42.190 align:middle line:90%
that that's women's work.

00:39:42.190 --> 00:39:48.450 align:middle line:84%
And in the old domination
system, being a man

00:39:48.450 --> 00:39:51.046 align:middle line:84%
is not being like
a woman, right?

00:39:51.046 --> 00:39:52.170 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's interesting.

00:39:52.170 --> 00:39:53.961 align:middle line:84%
That's an interesting
way of looking at it.

00:39:53.961 --> 00:39:56.440 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Yeah, so now that
the gender stereotypes--

00:39:56.440 --> 00:39:58.440 align:middle line:84%
and we're talking about
stereotypes, by the way.

00:39:58.440 --> 00:40:02.770 align:middle line:84%
So now we can see fathers who
are fathering the way that

00:40:02.770 --> 00:40:06.080 align:middle line:84%
used to be unfit for real
men-- diapering a baby,

00:40:06.080 --> 00:40:06.924 align:middle line:90%
feeding a baby.

00:40:06.924 --> 00:40:07.715 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:40:07.715 --> 00:40:11.800 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And it's only as the
status of women rose that men--

00:40:11.800 --> 00:40:13.540 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Have risen
to the occasion more.

00:40:13.540 --> 00:40:14.150 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: That's right.

00:40:14.150 --> 00:40:15.524 align:middle line:84%
Because they don't
feel that it's

00:40:15.524 --> 00:40:18.940 align:middle line:84%
such a devaluation of
them, of their status,

00:40:18.940 --> 00:40:22.230 align:middle line:84%
to embrace something more
stereotypically feminine.

00:40:22.230 --> 00:40:25.180 align:middle line:84%
So gender is a
big, ignored piece

00:40:25.180 --> 00:40:26.860 align:middle line:90%
that we had better look at.

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:28.770 align:middle line:84%
And I always make
the point which

00:40:28.770 --> 00:40:32.290 align:middle line:84%
is, people are uncomfortable
talking about gender.

00:40:32.290 --> 00:40:35.580 align:middle line:84%
But then, let's remember what
the great sociologist Louis

00:40:35.580 --> 00:40:36.460 align:middle line:90%
Wirth said.

00:40:36.460 --> 00:40:39.240 align:middle line:84%
He said the most important
things about a society

00:40:39.240 --> 00:40:41.830 align:middle line:84%
are those that people
don't want to talk about.

00:40:41.830 --> 00:40:43.910 align:middle line:90%
We saw it with race, didn't we?

00:40:43.910 --> 00:40:44.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, yes, right.

00:40:44.960 --> 00:40:46.400 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And we're
seeing it with gender.

00:40:46.400 --> 00:40:47.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Now it's gender, yes.

00:40:47.230 --> 00:40:48.771 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Only when
we talk about it,

00:40:48.771 --> 00:40:51.040 align:middle line:84%
when we put it out
in the open, can

00:40:51.040 --> 00:40:55.000 align:middle line:84%
we actually understand how
the dots are connected.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:58.100 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: My aunt was in a
great movie called "Mr. Mom"

00:40:58.100 --> 00:40:59.040 align:middle line:90%
a long time ago.

00:40:59.040 --> 00:41:01.460 align:middle line:84%
And again, it was
20 years ago where

00:41:01.460 --> 00:41:03.590 align:middle line:84%
that type of-- Michael
Keaton and Teri Garr.

00:41:03.590 --> 00:41:05.930 align:middle line:84%
They were in it in the--
it was all about that,

00:41:05.930 --> 00:41:08.890 align:middle line:84%
it was all about how the
male was taking over.

00:41:08.890 --> 00:41:10.670 align:middle line:84%
And it was an important
movie at the time.

00:41:10.670 --> 00:41:12.378 align:middle line:84%
Because it really
wasn't being done then.

00:41:12.378 --> 00:41:13.870 align:middle line:84%
It's being done
so much more now.

00:41:13.870 --> 00:41:17.740 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk a little
bit about caring economics

00:41:17.740 --> 00:41:19.416 align:middle line:84%
and how those two
relate together.

00:41:19.416 --> 00:41:21.540 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to take a
look at some slides here.

00:41:21.540 --> 00:41:26.500 align:middle line:84%
Making the economic case for
caring-- what exactly is that?

00:41:26.500 --> 00:41:27.910 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Well--

00:41:27.910 --> 00:41:29.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How children and
business and citizens

00:41:29.920 --> 00:41:35.010 align:middle line:84%
all need to work together,
or become one, and return

00:41:35.010 --> 00:41:36.070 align:middle line:90%
on that investment.

00:41:36.070 --> 00:41:39.200 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, it's a
huge return on investment.

00:41:39.200 --> 00:41:41.780 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
we've got to show.

00:41:41.780 --> 00:41:44.640 align:middle line:84%
And that's why we have, at the
Center for Partnership Studies,

00:41:44.640 --> 00:41:47.910 align:middle line:84%
launched the caring
economy campaign.

00:41:47.910 --> 00:41:50.740 align:middle line:84%
And we're soon going to
have-- the campaign will soon

00:41:50.740 --> 00:41:54.771 align:middle line:84%
have its own website,
caringeconomy.com.

00:41:54.771 --> 00:41:59.770 align:middle line:84%
And it will have a coalition of
major national organizations--

00:41:59.770 --> 00:42:03.380 align:middle line:84%
women's organizations certainly,
children's organizations,

00:42:03.380 --> 00:42:05.860 align:middle line:84%
think tanks, faith
organizations.

00:42:05.860 --> 00:42:08.310 align:middle line:84%
Because we have
to work together.

00:42:08.310 --> 00:42:10.900 align:middle line:84%
But we also have this training
program that I told you about.

00:42:10.900 --> 00:42:14.860 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, which is--
now, when people create

00:42:14.860 --> 00:42:17.030 align:middle line:84%
these types of policies,
when they create policies

00:42:17.030 --> 00:42:19.700 align:middle line:84%
where they're caring
for each other,

00:42:19.700 --> 00:42:22.700 align:middle line:84%
it changes the system
of our economics

00:42:22.700 --> 00:42:25.430 align:middle line:84%
because there are certain
organizations who have taken

00:42:25.430 --> 00:42:28.890 align:middle line:84%
on some of these caring
economics models.

00:42:28.890 --> 00:42:31.720 align:middle line:84%
You give, for example,
some organizations

00:42:31.720 --> 00:42:36.640 align:middle line:84%
that supply child care-- back
up child care programs-- that

00:42:36.640 --> 00:42:38.340 align:middle line:90%
actually are more successful.

00:42:38.340 --> 00:42:38.850 align:middle line:90%
They have--

00:42:38.850 --> 00:42:41.240 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, this is--
I bring out again, again,

00:42:41.240 --> 00:42:43.800 align:middle line:90%
in "The Real Wealth of Nations."

00:42:43.800 --> 00:42:47.680 align:middle line:84%
And it's information
that is up to us.

00:42:47.680 --> 00:42:49.730 align:middle line:84%
We have to change
the conversation.

00:42:49.730 --> 00:42:53.140 align:middle line:84%
Because people will tell you,
well, caring, that soft, fuzzy,

00:42:53.140 --> 00:42:56.000 align:middle line:84%
feminine stuff--
it's not effective.

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:59.680 align:middle line:84%
The reality is that it
is enormously effective.

00:42:59.680 --> 00:43:03.400 align:middle line:84%
And we have study after
study now showing that.

00:43:03.400 --> 00:43:07.850 align:middle line:84%
For example, the companies that
regularly appear in the Fortune

00:43:07.850 --> 00:43:11.710 align:middle line:84%
500 or the Working Mothers
as the best companies to work

00:43:11.710 --> 00:43:14.800 align:middle line:84%
for, they have more caring
policies-- child care,

00:43:14.800 --> 00:43:18.650 align:middle line:84%
good health care,
paid parental leave.

00:43:18.650 --> 00:43:21.810 align:middle line:84%
They have a higher, a
significantly higher,

00:43:21.810 --> 00:43:23.090 align:middle line:90%
return to investors.

00:43:23.090 --> 00:43:24.130 align:middle line:90%
It makes sense.

00:43:24.130 --> 00:43:27.160 align:middle line:84%
When people feel that they and
their families are cared for,

00:43:27.160 --> 00:43:28.610 align:middle line:84%
they're going to
work very hard so

00:43:28.610 --> 00:43:30.144 align:middle line:90%
that that company is successful.

00:43:30.144 --> 00:43:32.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: They feel
supported, so therefore they

00:43:32.060 --> 00:43:32.990 align:middle line:90%
support the company.

00:43:32.990 --> 00:43:33.865 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Absolutely.

00:43:33.865 --> 00:43:36.920 align:middle line:84%
And it happens not only
on the business level,

00:43:36.920 --> 00:43:38.670 align:middle line:90%
but on the national level.

00:43:38.670 --> 00:43:40.950 align:middle line:84%
And I think that we're going
to be talking about that.

00:43:40.950 --> 00:43:42.400 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, absolutely.

00:43:42.400 --> 00:43:44.290 align:middle line:84%
So well, let's actually
talk about that now.

00:43:44.290 --> 00:43:46.670 align:middle line:84%
On the national level,
how would that affect us?

00:43:46.670 --> 00:43:49.786 align:middle line:84%
We see that in corporations
like we just saw, but how would

00:43:49.786 --> 00:43:51.160 align:middle line:84%
it affect us at
a national level?

00:43:51.160 --> 00:43:53.315 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, we have
models for that, too.

00:43:53.315 --> 00:43:55.070 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Good.

00:43:55.070 --> 00:43:58.670 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: It's all there,
if we just really look

00:43:58.670 --> 00:44:01.760 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the lenses of the
partnership versus domination,

00:44:01.760 --> 00:44:06.834 align:middle line:84%
of a caring or uncaring
economy, that go with each.

00:44:06.834 --> 00:44:08.250 align:middle line:84%
As I said, there's
been a movement

00:44:08.250 --> 00:44:10.940 align:middle line:84%
towards the
partnership side, or we

00:44:10.940 --> 00:44:14.690 align:middle line:84%
wouldn't have, for
example, child labor laws.

00:44:14.690 --> 00:44:16.990 align:middle line:84%
Or we wouldn't have
any of the things

00:44:16.990 --> 00:44:20.100 align:middle line:84%
that we have--
safety regulations.

00:44:20.100 --> 00:44:23.130 align:middle line:84%
Because in pure domination
systems, well, you had slavery.

00:44:23.130 --> 00:44:24.800 align:middle line:84%
The Greeks, for
example, with all

00:44:24.800 --> 00:44:26.480 align:middle line:84%
of their-- the
Athenians, with all

00:44:26.480 --> 00:44:29.910 align:middle line:84%
of their talk about democracy,
they were a slave society.

00:44:29.910 --> 00:44:31.870 align:middle line:90%
There were no protections there.

00:44:31.870 --> 00:44:34.340 align:middle line:84%
But as we have
moved, some nations

00:44:34.340 --> 00:44:35.610 align:middle line:90%
have been in the forefront.

00:44:35.610 --> 00:44:38.130 align:middle line:84%
And these have been
nations like Sweden,

00:44:38.130 --> 00:44:41.610 align:middle line:84%
like Finland, like Norway, like
Iceland-- which, by the way,

00:44:41.610 --> 00:44:42.290 align:middle line:90%
have recovered.

00:44:42.290 --> 00:44:45.460 align:middle line:84%
Except-- Iceland
the bankers did in,

00:44:45.460 --> 00:44:47.280 align:middle line:84%
but they have
recovered, all of them,

00:44:47.280 --> 00:44:49.240 align:middle line:84%
from the recession,
the great recession,

00:44:49.240 --> 00:44:51.270 align:middle line:84%
much better than
the United States.

00:44:51.270 --> 00:44:54.330 align:middle line:84%
And one of the
reasons is that they

00:44:54.330 --> 00:44:57.500 align:middle line:90%
have invested in their people.

00:44:57.500 --> 00:44:59.580 align:middle line:84%
Now, these nations--
think about it.

00:44:59.580 --> 00:45:01.250 align:middle line:84%
At the beginning of
the 20th century,

00:45:01.250 --> 00:45:04.390 align:middle line:84%
they were so poor that
there were famines.

00:45:04.390 --> 00:45:05.990 align:middle line:90%
Whole states got populated--

00:45:05.990 --> 00:45:07.030 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, right.

00:45:07.030 --> 00:45:08.270 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: --Minnesota.

00:45:08.270 --> 00:45:12.290 align:middle line:84%
Today they are invariably
in the highest ranks,

00:45:12.290 --> 00:45:15.750 align:middle line:84%
not only of the human
development reports

00:45:15.750 --> 00:45:19.910 align:middle line:84%
of the United Nations, but
of the World Economic Forum's

00:45:19.910 --> 00:45:22.700 align:middle line:90%
global competitiveness reports.

00:45:22.700 --> 00:45:24.130 align:middle line:90%
So what happened?

00:45:24.130 --> 00:45:28.020 align:middle line:84%
One of the main reasons
is that, as I said,

00:45:28.020 --> 00:45:31.020 align:middle line:90%
they moved to a caring economy.

00:45:31.020 --> 00:45:34.500 align:middle line:84%
They have a mix of socialism,
yes, of central planning,

00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:36.920 align:middle line:84%
and a very healthy
market economy.

00:45:36.920 --> 00:45:40.390 align:middle line:84%
But they often call
themselves caring societies.

00:45:40.390 --> 00:45:44.060 align:middle line:84%
They have very generous
paid parental leave.

00:45:44.060 --> 00:45:48.950 align:middle line:84%
They have-- for both mothers
and fathers, by the way.

00:45:48.950 --> 00:45:51.960 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: There's a clip that
we have that the Center

00:45:51.960 --> 00:45:54.660 align:middle line:84%
for Partnership Studies
put together of a study

00:45:54.660 --> 00:45:56.840 align:middle line:84%
that they specifically
did around this.

00:45:56.840 --> 00:46:00.632 align:middle line:84%
And it's Men and Women and
the Global Equality of Life.

00:46:00.632 --> 00:46:02.340 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: We did that
study at the Center

00:46:02.340 --> 00:46:03.610 align:middle line:90%
for Partnership Studies.

00:46:03.610 --> 00:46:06.290 align:middle line:84%
It's Women, Men, and the
Global Quality of Life.

00:46:06.290 --> 00:46:08.690 align:middle line:84%
And it documents
something that it's really

00:46:08.690 --> 00:46:13.410 align:middle line:84%
our job to make
people understand.

00:46:13.410 --> 00:46:16.220 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to start by giving
you some empirical evidence

00:46:16.220 --> 00:46:16.740 align:middle line:90%
of this.

00:46:16.740 --> 00:46:20.750 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to start with
some statistical studies.

00:46:20.750 --> 00:46:23.260 align:middle line:84%
We, at the Center for
Partnership Studies, which

00:46:23.260 --> 00:46:28.430 align:middle line:84%
is the organization, the not for
profit, that I'm president of,

00:46:28.430 --> 00:46:32.865 align:middle line:84%
did a study comparing
two bundles of measures

00:46:32.865 --> 00:46:36.270 align:middle line:90%
from 89 nations in our world.

00:46:36.270 --> 00:46:39.680 align:middle line:84%
One bundle looked
at quality of life.

00:46:39.680 --> 00:46:43.260 align:middle line:84%
The other bundle looked
at the status of women.

00:46:43.260 --> 00:46:46.230 align:middle line:84%
So we were looking at
matters in quality of life

00:46:46.230 --> 00:46:48.140 align:middle line:84%
all the way from
infant mortality,

00:46:48.140 --> 00:46:51.790 align:middle line:84%
to the gap between income
on top and on bottom,

00:46:51.790 --> 00:46:54.740 align:middle line:84%
to human rights ratings,
environmental ratings.

00:46:54.740 --> 00:46:57.650 align:middle line:84%
And we found, in
this study, which

00:46:57.650 --> 00:47:01.600 align:middle line:84%
is called Women, Men, and
the Global Quality of Life,

00:47:01.600 --> 00:47:06.660 align:middle line:84%
that the status of women
can, in significant respects,

00:47:06.660 --> 00:47:10.670 align:middle line:84%
be a better predictor of
the general quality of life

00:47:10.670 --> 00:47:14.280 align:middle line:90%
of a society than GDP.

00:47:14.280 --> 00:47:16.655 align:middle line:84%
Which is of course the
conventional measure that we

00:47:16.655 --> 00:47:21.560 align:middle line:84%
all keep being told would
measure economic health.

00:47:21.560 --> 00:47:23.970 align:middle line:90%
And that's not the only study.

00:47:23.970 --> 00:47:27.280 align:middle line:84%
The World Values
Surveys-- in 2000,

00:47:27.280 --> 00:47:30.130 align:middle line:84%
they finally decided
to look at gender.

00:47:30.130 --> 00:47:34.640 align:middle line:84%
And they found that those
world regions-- and this

00:47:34.640 --> 00:47:39.800 align:middle line:84%
was, again, a study of values
worldwide-- that those world

00:47:39.800 --> 00:47:42.680 align:middle line:84%
regions where the
status of women

00:47:42.680 --> 00:47:46.740 align:middle line:84%
is higher, where women are not
viewed as having to be confined

00:47:46.740 --> 00:47:50.820 align:middle line:84%
under male control in the
household, that not only

00:47:50.820 --> 00:47:53.030 align:middle line:84%
was there a higher
quality of life,

00:47:53.030 --> 00:47:56.910 align:middle line:84%
but more civil rights
and more democracy.

00:47:56.910 --> 00:47:58.560 align:middle line:84%
A third study-- and
again, these are

00:47:58.560 --> 00:48:02.040 align:middle line:84%
all quantitative,
statistical studies--

00:48:02.040 --> 00:48:08.580 align:middle line:84%
is the gender gap study
that is now annually being

00:48:08.580 --> 00:48:11.347 align:middle line:84%
done by the World
Economic Forum.

00:48:11.347 --> 00:48:14.430 align:middle line:84%
And again, if you
look at the findings,

00:48:14.430 --> 00:48:17.230 align:middle line:84%
you see that those nations
that have the smallest gender

00:48:17.230 --> 00:48:20.090 align:middle line:84%
gap-- because unfortunately,
every nation in our world

00:48:20.090 --> 00:48:23.630 align:middle line:84%
still has one-- that those
are the nations where there

00:48:23.630 --> 00:48:27.770 align:middle line:84%
is a higher general
quality of life.

00:48:27.770 --> 00:48:29.390 align:middle line:90%
Now, why is this?

00:48:29.390 --> 00:48:31.020 align:middle line:84%
Of course, there
are many reasons.

00:48:31.020 --> 00:48:33.260 align:middle line:90%
One is very simple.

00:48:33.260 --> 00:48:36.940 align:middle line:90%
Women are half the population.

00:48:36.940 --> 00:48:39.580 align:middle line:84%
But not only are we
half the population,

00:48:39.580 --> 00:48:42.090 align:middle line:84%
but we are the
half that is still

00:48:42.090 --> 00:48:46.390 align:middle line:84%
entrusted with caring
for young children.

00:48:46.390 --> 00:48:51.080 align:middle line:84%
So when a society deprives,
as so many world cultures

00:48:51.080 --> 00:48:54.810 align:middle line:84%
still do, with traditions
of horrible discrimination

00:48:54.810 --> 00:48:58.680 align:middle line:84%
against girls and women--
not only equal health care,

00:48:58.680 --> 00:49:02.150 align:middle line:84%
equal food, equal
education, we're really

00:49:02.150 --> 00:49:06.062 align:middle line:84%
affecting future
generations, aren't we?

00:49:06.062 --> 00:49:10.920 align:middle line:84%
Well, I think this whole thing
about the status of women--

00:49:10.920 --> 00:49:13.830 align:middle line:84%
remember, when
you saw that clip,

00:49:13.830 --> 00:49:16.330 align:middle line:84%
that that's one of
the components that

00:49:16.330 --> 00:49:19.380 align:middle line:84%
is very important in
whether a society orients

00:49:19.380 --> 00:49:23.480 align:middle line:84%
to the domination system
or the partnership system.

00:49:23.480 --> 00:49:28.120 align:middle line:84%
And in these Nordic nations
that we just talked about,

00:49:28.120 --> 00:49:31.640 align:middle line:84%
women are 40%--
four zero percent--

00:49:31.640 --> 00:49:33.790 align:middle line:90%
of the national legislature.

00:49:33.790 --> 00:49:34.674 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow, amazing.

00:49:34.674 --> 00:49:36.840 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: All right, well,
we should be 50%, really.

00:49:36.840 --> 00:49:38.107 align:middle line:90%
We're half the population.

00:49:38.107 --> 00:49:38.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:49:38.690 --> 00:49:41.640 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: But the
point of it is this:

00:49:41.640 --> 00:49:46.490 align:middle line:84%
it's not only women who voted
for more caring policies-- men.

00:49:46.490 --> 00:49:50.340 align:middle line:84%
It's because as the
status of women rises,

00:49:50.340 --> 00:49:53.570 align:middle line:84%
men no longer feel it's such
a threat to their status,

00:49:53.570 --> 00:49:57.130 align:middle line:84%
to their quote,
masculinity, to embrace

00:49:57.130 --> 00:50:01.260 align:middle line:84%
these more feminine,
more caring policies.

00:50:01.260 --> 00:50:03.810 align:middle line:84%
And this did not
happen in a vacuum.

00:50:03.810 --> 00:50:05.230 align:middle line:90%
I really want to say this.

00:50:05.230 --> 00:50:07.630 align:middle line:84%
It happened because
these nations moved more

00:50:07.630 --> 00:50:09.330 align:middle line:90%
to the partnership side.

00:50:09.330 --> 00:50:13.030 align:middle line:84%
They have much more
democracy and equality

00:50:13.030 --> 00:50:15.400 align:middle line:84%
in both the family
and the state.

00:50:15.400 --> 00:50:17.885 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So there's not as
much of a gender gap there.

00:50:17.885 --> 00:50:19.260 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Not as
much of a gender

00:50:19.260 --> 00:50:21.390 align:middle line:84%
gap, but that's not
the only factor.

00:50:21.390 --> 00:50:23.580 align:middle line:84%
For example, they also
are in the forefront

00:50:23.580 --> 00:50:26.690 align:middle line:84%
in the world--
remember when I said

00:50:26.690 --> 00:50:29.350 align:middle line:84%
force fear is part of
a domination system?

00:50:29.350 --> 00:50:30.830 align:middle line:90%
It keeps it together?

00:50:30.830 --> 00:50:33.610 align:middle line:84%
They're at the
forefront of trying

00:50:33.610 --> 00:50:35.210 align:middle line:84%
to leave those
traditions behind.

00:50:35.210 --> 00:50:39.060 align:middle line:84%
The first peace studies came
out of the Nordic nations.

00:50:39.060 --> 00:50:43.510 align:middle line:84%
The first laws saying
that it's against the law

00:50:43.510 --> 00:50:46.366 align:middle line:84%
to use physical discipline
against children and families--

00:50:46.366 --> 00:50:47.990 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Came out of
the Nordic nations?

00:50:47.990 --> 00:50:50.198 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Yes, and they also
have a very strong men's

00:50:50.198 --> 00:50:54.590 align:middle line:84%
movement to disentangle quote,
masculinity, from its dominator

00:50:54.590 --> 00:50:57.260 align:middle line:84%
entanglement with
domination, with violence,

00:50:57.260 --> 00:50:58.970 align:middle line:90%
that that's the real man.

00:50:58.970 --> 00:51:01.840 align:middle line:84%
So it's because they've
moved in that direction.

00:51:01.840 --> 00:51:05.070 align:middle line:84%
But again, if we really
still marginalize

00:51:05.070 --> 00:51:09.390 align:middle line:84%
these so-called women's
issues, we're missing the boat.

00:51:09.390 --> 00:51:15.680 align:middle line:84%
We can't understand that it's--
as long as women are ranked

00:51:15.680 --> 00:51:20.990 align:middle line:84%
as inferior to men, as long as
men are supposed to dominate

00:51:20.990 --> 00:51:23.520 align:middle line:84%
women, which is what
a lot of the gender--

00:51:23.520 --> 00:51:25.660 align:middle line:84%
the war of the sexes
is about, really.

00:51:25.660 --> 00:51:27.730 align:middle line:84%
Women manipulate,
because they're not

00:51:27.730 --> 00:51:30.040 align:middle line:90%
supposed to control.

00:51:30.040 --> 00:51:33.730 align:middle line:84%
But as long as women are
devalued, so also will

00:51:33.730 --> 00:51:38.670 align:middle line:84%
these stereotypically
feminine, caring, care giving,

00:51:38.670 --> 00:51:42.760 align:middle line:84%
nonviolence-- it's not realistic
to expect more caring policies

00:51:42.760 --> 00:51:47.620 align:middle line:84%
as long as we don't really
globally, globally raise

00:51:47.620 --> 00:51:48.587 align:middle line:90%
the status of women.

00:51:48.587 --> 00:51:50.170 align:middle line:84%
Now, the good news
is that there's now

00:51:50.170 --> 00:51:51.930 align:middle line:90%
a Global Women's Movement.

00:51:51.930 --> 00:51:53.930 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How is that
affecting the United States?

00:51:53.930 --> 00:51:55.805 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, the
United States, of course,

00:51:55.805 --> 00:51:56.990 align:middle line:90%
has been in a regression.

00:51:56.990 --> 00:52:00.560 align:middle line:84%
Whereas all the other
industrialized nations

00:52:00.560 --> 00:52:04.700 align:middle line:84%
have been moving more
towards caring policies,

00:52:04.700 --> 00:52:07.360 align:middle line:84%
we have been moving
back from them.

00:52:07.360 --> 00:52:11.470 align:middle line:84%
And this whole-- really, it's a
red herring about the deficit.

00:52:11.470 --> 00:52:14.600 align:middle line:84%
Because it's a
question of priorities.

00:52:14.600 --> 00:52:18.520 align:middle line:84%
Do we give corporate
welfare or do

00:52:18.520 --> 00:52:21.380 align:middle line:84%
we invest in early
childhood education?

00:52:21.380 --> 00:52:23.380 align:middle line:84%
Now, I want to make a
very important point here,

00:52:23.380 --> 00:52:25.600 align:middle line:84%
because I always
believe that you've

00:52:25.600 --> 00:52:30.680 align:middle line:84%
got to show people who are
very much in this old paradigm

00:52:30.680 --> 00:52:33.420 align:middle line:90%
that caring is successful.

00:52:33.420 --> 00:52:36.730 align:middle line:84%
And as we move-- and
this is really basic--

00:52:36.730 --> 00:52:41.640 align:middle line:84%
we are moving into a whole
new technological age,

00:52:41.640 --> 00:52:45.560 align:middle line:84%
the so-called
post-industrial era,

00:52:45.560 --> 00:52:47.720 align:middle line:90%
from the manufacturing era.

00:52:47.720 --> 00:52:50.470 align:middle line:84%
Robotics is coming down
the road, automation.

00:52:50.470 --> 00:52:53.890 align:middle line:84%
A lot of the manufacturing
jobs never will come back.

00:52:53.890 --> 00:52:56.090 align:middle line:84%
Economists never
tire of telling us

00:52:56.090 --> 00:53:00.480 align:middle line:84%
that the most important capital
for this knowledge service

00:53:00.480 --> 00:53:05.210 align:middle line:84%
post-industrial economy is
high quality, human capital.

00:53:05.210 --> 00:53:10.230 align:middle line:84%
As we discussed, it
starts in early childhood.

00:53:10.230 --> 00:53:14.530 align:middle line:84%
If we don't invest in
caring for our children,

00:53:14.530 --> 00:53:19.000 align:middle line:84%
in parenting education, in
high quality early childhood

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:25.560 align:middle line:84%
education, in paid parental
leave, in health care,

00:53:25.560 --> 00:53:30.040 align:middle line:84%
in-- this country has the
highest child poverty rates,

00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:34.580 align:middle line:84%
this wealthy United States,
of any developed nation,

00:53:34.580 --> 00:53:37.059 align:middle line:84%
as well as the highest
maternal mortality rates.

00:53:37.059 --> 00:53:38.100 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I knew that, yes.

00:53:38.100 --> 00:53:39.910 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Now, what
does that tell us?

00:53:39.910 --> 00:53:40.896 align:middle line:90%


00:53:40.896 --> 00:53:42.460 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Undervalued.

00:53:42.460 --> 00:53:44.780 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: The nations that
I'm talking about now--

00:53:44.780 --> 00:53:48.340 align:middle line:84%
Sweden, Finland, Norway--
have very low poverty rates,

00:53:48.340 --> 00:53:51.800 align:middle line:84%
very low woman
headed poverty rates,

00:53:51.800 --> 00:53:53.600 align:middle line:84%
woman-headed family
poverty rates.

00:53:53.600 --> 00:53:55.308 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Do you attribute
that to the fact

00:53:55.308 --> 00:53:58.900 align:middle line:84%
that that is more of a
female-dominated system?

00:53:58.900 --> 00:54:00.760 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: It's not
female dominated.

00:54:00.760 --> 00:54:02.465 align:middle line:90%
Women are only 40%, anyway.

00:54:02.465 --> 00:54:03.340 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, right.

00:54:03.340 --> 00:54:04.090 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: It's hardly that.

00:54:04.090 --> 00:54:05.798 align:middle line:84%
I attribute that to
the fact that they've

00:54:05.798 --> 00:54:09.300 align:middle line:84%
moved to more gender equity,
to more gender balance,

00:54:09.300 --> 00:54:12.820 align:middle line:84%
and to the fact that they've
moved more to the partnership

00:54:12.820 --> 00:54:17.650 align:middle line:84%
configuration, of which
gender is an important piece.

00:54:17.650 --> 00:54:20.670 align:middle line:84%
And I think we really have
to pay attention to that.

00:54:20.670 --> 00:54:25.780 align:middle line:84%
Because those nations have
very successful economies

00:54:25.780 --> 00:54:28.610 align:middle line:84%
and very low crime
rates, for example.

00:54:28.610 --> 00:54:31.220 align:middle line:84%
And I started to
say that they have

00:54:31.220 --> 00:54:32.822 align:middle line:90%
a lot of woman-headed families.

00:54:32.822 --> 00:54:34.280 align:middle line:84%
We're always being
told that that's

00:54:34.280 --> 00:54:36.020 align:middle line:90%
the problem with poverty.

00:54:36.020 --> 00:54:40.140 align:middle line:84%
But they have very low,
very low poverty rates

00:54:40.140 --> 00:54:42.650 align:middle line:84%
for woman-headed
families because they

00:54:42.650 --> 00:54:45.337 align:middle line:84%
have the social
support for caring.

00:54:45.337 --> 00:54:47.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Women-headed families
meaning that the female is

00:54:47.670 --> 00:54:48.590 align:middle line:90%
the primary--

00:54:48.590 --> 00:54:50.132 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: That's
right, that's right.

00:54:50.132 --> 00:54:50.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --earner.

00:54:50.840 --> 00:54:51.490 align:middle line:90%
I understand.

00:54:51.490 --> 00:54:53.520 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now in the
United States, though,

00:54:53.520 --> 00:54:57.880 align:middle line:84%
we have dual-income families,
many, many-- so this is--

00:54:57.880 --> 00:55:01.580 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: So also in Sweden
and Norway, by the way.

00:55:01.580 --> 00:55:03.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But what we
don't have is the systems

00:55:03.670 --> 00:55:06.450 align:middle line:84%
that support the
dual-income families?

00:55:06.450 --> 00:55:08.920 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: That's really
what we're talking about,

00:55:08.920 --> 00:55:12.660 align:middle line:84%
is do we support
caring and care giving?

00:55:12.660 --> 00:55:15.390 align:middle line:90%
Do we have caring policies?

00:55:15.390 --> 00:55:17.790 align:middle line:84%
And I think that we
better understand

00:55:17.790 --> 00:55:21.090 align:middle line:84%
that we have to start with
different measures of what

00:55:21.090 --> 00:55:22.665 align:middle line:90%
is economically productive.

00:55:22.665 --> 00:55:24.290 align:middle line:84%
And that's something
that we're working

00:55:24.290 --> 00:55:28.090 align:middle line:84%
on through our Center for
Partnership Studies Caring

00:55:28.090 --> 00:55:29.810 align:middle line:90%
Economy Campaign.

00:55:29.810 --> 00:55:34.170 align:middle line:84%
Because the old measures--
GDP, Gross Domestic Product--

00:55:34.170 --> 00:55:36.090 align:middle line:90%
are crazy.

00:55:36.090 --> 00:55:39.316 align:middle line:84%
They include activities
that harm and take life.

00:55:39.316 --> 00:55:40.190 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Explain that.

00:55:40.190 --> 00:55:41.160 align:middle line:90%


00:55:41.160 --> 00:55:44.300 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Making cigarettes--
the medical costs,

00:55:44.300 --> 00:55:49.040 align:middle line:84%
the funeral costs--
they're all great for GDP.

00:55:49.040 --> 00:55:52.710 align:middle line:84%
Oil spills-- wonderful for
GDP-- the cleanup costs,

00:55:52.710 --> 00:55:53.850 align:middle line:90%
the lawsuits.

00:55:53.850 --> 00:55:57.600 align:middle line:84%
But not only-- and this is
the point, now-- not only

00:55:57.600 --> 00:56:03.780 align:middle line:84%
do these old measures include
as positive negatives,

00:56:03.780 --> 00:56:07.410 align:middle line:84%
they fail to include
as productive work

00:56:07.410 --> 00:56:10.910 align:middle line:84%
in their measures of so-called
economic health the most

00:56:10.910 --> 00:56:14.650 align:middle line:84%
important human work,
the life-sustaining work.

00:56:14.650 --> 00:56:21.850 align:middle line:84%
So I've proposed, really, a
full spectrum economic map

00:56:21.850 --> 00:56:26.330 align:middle line:84%
that doesn't just include
the market, the government,

00:56:26.330 --> 00:56:29.490 align:middle line:84%
and the legal economy, but that
also includes the household

00:56:29.490 --> 00:56:36.270 align:middle line:84%
economy, the unpaid
volunteer economy,

00:56:36.270 --> 00:56:38.970 align:middle line:90%
and the natural economy.

00:56:38.970 --> 00:56:41.630 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, very important to
include-- very, very important

00:56:41.630 --> 00:56:42.180 align:middle line:90%
to include.

00:56:42.180 --> 00:56:46.980 align:middle line:84%
How do you think that our media
shapes women in the world,

00:56:46.980 --> 00:56:48.560 align:middle line:90%
here in the US specifically?

00:56:48.560 --> 00:56:51.560 align:middle line:84%
And how does that compare
to other countries?

00:56:51.560 --> 00:56:54.320 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, of course, we've
exported a lot of our media.

00:56:54.320 --> 00:56:57.640 align:middle line:84%
So by now I don't think
that any country--

00:56:57.640 --> 00:56:58.640 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, that's true.

00:56:58.640 --> 00:56:59.120 align:middle line:90%
Yes, this is true.

00:56:59.120 --> 00:56:59.523 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:56:59.523 --> 00:57:00.773 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: --is immune from us.

00:57:00.773 --> 00:57:04.370 align:middle line:84%
But I'll tell you, years
ago when I was in Denmark--

00:57:04.370 --> 00:57:06.329 align:middle line:84%
I don't know what
the situation is now.

00:57:06.329 --> 00:57:08.245 align:middle line:84%
It's one of those nations,
the Nordic nations,

00:57:08.245 --> 00:57:11.870 align:middle line:84%
that are doing so much better,
have more equality, et cetera.

00:57:11.870 --> 00:57:13.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: More progressive, yes.

00:57:13.820 --> 00:57:16.480 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: They didn't show
the kind of television

00:57:16.480 --> 00:57:17.257 align:middle line:90%
that we show.

00:57:17.257 --> 00:57:18.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: They didn't.

00:57:18.090 --> 00:57:20.650 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: But probably
by today they do.

00:57:20.650 --> 00:57:23.455 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well I notice
when I-- as I said,

00:57:23.455 --> 00:57:24.330 align:middle line:90%
I have a young child.

00:57:24.330 --> 00:57:27.100 align:middle line:84%
And I-- on my drive to school
I've had to change my route

00:57:27.100 --> 00:57:31.900 align:middle line:84%
because there are pornography
ads on the side of the road.

00:57:31.900 --> 00:57:34.650 align:middle line:84%
There's even network
television ads

00:57:34.650 --> 00:57:38.790 align:middle line:84%
that are showing more and
more examples of women just

00:57:38.790 --> 00:57:45.120 align:middle line:84%
being symbols rather than
human beings any longer.

00:57:45.120 --> 00:57:48.840 align:middle line:84%
So I can only avoid
those routes for so long.

00:57:48.840 --> 00:57:50.950 align:middle line:84%
There has to be a
conversation that goes along

00:57:50.950 --> 00:57:54.640 align:middle line:84%
with it, that has to
explain to my young daughter

00:57:54.640 --> 00:57:58.600 align:middle line:84%
that a woman is more
than a sex symbol.

00:57:58.600 --> 00:58:00.730 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: You know,
the objectification

00:58:00.730 --> 00:58:04.790 align:middle line:84%
of the human beings is part
of the domination system.

00:58:04.790 --> 00:58:09.300 align:middle line:84%
It's an instrumental view
of another human being, one

00:58:09.300 --> 00:58:10.760 align:middle line:90%
that you can control.

00:58:10.760 --> 00:58:12.820 align:middle line:90%
It unfortunately is not new.

00:58:12.820 --> 00:58:14.000 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, right, right.

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:15.416 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: This is
something that--

00:58:15.416 --> 00:58:17.880 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's just the
line has gotten blurred.

00:58:17.880 --> 00:58:20.570 align:middle line:84%
It's been pushed
more and more lately.

00:58:20.570 --> 00:58:22.800 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, it's
an interesting thing.

