01:18:15.910 --> 01:18:16.868 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: In the media.

01:18:16.868 --> 01:18:19.290 align:middle line:84%
Well, for some reason I
thought of Jane Fonda, who

01:18:19.290 --> 01:18:21.710 align:middle line:90%
really left Ted Turner because--

01:18:21.710 --> 01:18:22.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

01:18:22.500 --> 01:18:24.080 align:middle line:84%
There are many, if
you start to look.

01:18:24.080 --> 01:18:25.900 align:middle line:90%
Yes, absolutely.

01:18:25.900 --> 01:18:29.900 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: But the woman
who did the film, Newsom,

01:18:29.900 --> 01:18:32.990 align:middle line:84%
the wife of the mayor of--
former mayor of San Francisco.

01:18:32.990 --> 01:18:34.610 align:middle line:90%
He's now lieutenant governor.

01:18:34.610 --> 01:18:36.470 align:middle line:84%
She's the one who did
"Miss Representation."

01:18:36.470 --> 01:18:39.530 align:middle line:84%
They seem to have a
partnership relationship.

01:18:39.530 --> 01:18:42.790 align:middle line:84%
The Clintons seem to have
a partnership relationship,

01:18:42.790 --> 01:18:46.230 align:middle line:84%
despite his terrible
sexual addiction.

01:18:46.230 --> 01:18:48.220 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah,
that's brave to say.

01:18:48.220 --> 01:18:52.530 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Yeah, but he
respects her as a human being.

01:18:52.530 --> 01:18:54.000 align:middle line:90%
He didn't respect her as a wife.

01:18:54.000 --> 01:18:55.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Do you
know that for sure?

01:18:55.440 --> 01:18:57.440 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: I think
so, because he really

01:18:57.440 --> 01:19:01.290 align:middle line:90%
has supported her career.

01:19:01.290 --> 01:19:02.960 align:middle line:90%
And that's really what we want.

01:19:02.960 --> 01:19:05.970 align:middle line:84%
We want both men and women
to be able to express

01:19:05.970 --> 01:19:10.570 align:middle line:84%
their full humanity, to express
their capacities for creating,

01:19:10.570 --> 01:19:12.877 align:middle line:84%
for working outside
of the home--

01:19:12.877 --> 01:19:13.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: For being leaders.

01:19:13.960 --> 01:19:15.335 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --for
being leaders, at

01:19:15.335 --> 01:19:18.460 align:middle line:84%
the same time that they can
express their capacities

01:19:18.460 --> 01:19:22.660 align:middle line:84%
for caring and for nurturing
and for that caring connection

01:19:22.660 --> 01:19:24.370 align:middle line:90%
that we all so yearn for.

01:19:24.370 --> 01:19:27.790 align:middle line:84%
That it is not possible
in a domination system--

01:19:27.790 --> 01:19:30.750 align:middle line:84%
only possible as
we empower women,

01:19:30.750 --> 01:19:33.910 align:middle line:84%
as we move more towards
the partnership side.

01:19:33.910 --> 01:19:34.670 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

01:19:34.670 --> 01:19:36.990 align:middle line:84%
There is an example
here in this next clip

01:19:36.990 --> 01:19:39.680 align:middle line:84%
of how the mother
and the child bond

01:19:39.680 --> 01:19:43.274 align:middle line:84%
has been kind of deleted
from certain situations,

01:19:43.274 --> 01:19:44.440 align:middle line:90%
where you can see this here.

01:19:44.440 --> 01:19:45.855 align:middle line:90%
And it gives us an example.

01:19:45.855 --> 01:19:48.690 align:middle line:90%


01:19:48.690 --> 01:19:50.850 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: I want
young people to have

01:19:50.850 --> 01:19:54.900 align:middle line:84%
the benefit of the new
scholarship on evolution,

01:19:54.900 --> 01:19:59.970 align:middle line:84%
scholarship that shows the
importance of cooperation, not

01:19:59.970 --> 01:20:04.540 align:middle line:84%
just fierce competition,
in evolution.

01:20:04.540 --> 01:20:10.380 align:middle line:84%
I think that they're entitled
to know that women were there,

01:20:10.380 --> 01:20:12.730 align:middle line:84%
which you really
wouldn't know if you look

01:20:12.730 --> 01:20:17.140 align:middle line:84%
at the conventional texts
and at the museum dioramas.

01:20:17.140 --> 01:20:18.845 align:middle line:90%
We're just not present.

01:20:18.845 --> 01:20:22.990 align:middle line:84%
That in fact, mother
child bonds were

01:20:22.990 --> 01:20:25.430 align:middle line:84%
one of the most
important aspects

01:20:25.430 --> 01:20:27.780 align:middle line:90%
of the evolution of love.

01:20:27.780 --> 01:20:30.420 align:middle line:84%
Because by the
grace of evolution,

01:20:30.420 --> 01:20:35.500 align:middle line:84%
we humans receive biochemical
rewards of enormous pleasure,

01:20:35.500 --> 01:20:38.890 align:middle line:84%
not only when we are
loved or cared for,

01:20:38.890 --> 01:20:43.770 align:middle line:84%
but also when we love or care
for another, be it a child,

01:20:43.770 --> 01:20:47.620 align:middle line:84%
be it a friend, be it a
lover, be it even a pet.

01:20:47.620 --> 01:20:49.710 align:middle line:84%
We all have experienced
this, but it's

01:20:49.710 --> 01:20:52.330 align:middle line:84%
left out of the
conventional narratives.

01:20:52.330 --> 01:20:54.300 align:middle line:90%
And it needs to be put in.

01:20:54.300 --> 01:20:56.620 align:middle line:84%
And we're back, really,
to "Tomorrow's Children"

01:20:56.620 --> 01:21:00.810 align:middle line:84%
and to what I call teaching
meaningful evolution,

01:21:00.810 --> 01:21:07.060 align:middle line:84%
showing it contrary to what
we see so much emphasized

01:21:07.060 --> 01:21:09.740 align:middle line:84%
to our capacity for
violence-- which

01:21:09.740 --> 01:21:12.012 align:middle line:84%
we have, as human
beings, women, too.

01:21:12.012 --> 01:21:13.470 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's part
of survival, yes.

01:21:13.470 --> 01:21:16.315 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well,
it's part of-- today

01:21:16.315 --> 01:21:18.180 align:middle line:84%
it isn't very much
part of survival.

01:21:18.180 --> 01:21:19.991 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, an old
part of old survival.

01:21:19.991 --> 01:21:21.490 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Maybe if
you were-- but we

01:21:21.490 --> 01:21:23.870 align:middle line:84%
don't have any saber tooth
tigers around the corner.

01:21:23.870 --> 01:21:26.110 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But our DNA
doesn't know that.

01:21:26.110 --> 01:21:28.130 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Our DNA
does know that.

01:21:28.130 --> 01:21:30.360 align:middle line:90%
DNA does change.

01:21:30.360 --> 01:21:35.210 align:middle line:84%
And the thing that
counts is the interaction

01:21:35.210 --> 01:21:37.740 align:middle line:84%
of our genes with
our experiences.

01:21:37.740 --> 01:21:40.490 align:middle line:84%
And our experiences
are culturally shaped,

01:21:40.490 --> 01:21:44.650 align:middle line:84%
as mediated by families,
education, religion, politics,

01:21:44.650 --> 01:21:45.150 align:middle line:90%
economics.

01:21:45.150 --> 01:21:46.390 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's a
good point, yes.

01:21:46.390 --> 01:21:47.380 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Everything that
we've talked about-- well,

01:21:47.380 --> 01:21:48.510 align:middle line:90%
we know this from science.

01:21:48.510 --> 01:21:49.100 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, that's true.

01:21:49.100 --> 01:21:49.599 align:middle line:90%
Epigenetics.

01:21:49.599 --> 01:21:50.380 align:middle line:90%
You are right.

01:21:50.380 --> 01:21:52.110 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: So we
really need to change

01:21:52.110 --> 01:21:55.760 align:middle line:84%
the way we teach
evolution and emphasize

01:21:55.760 --> 01:22:00.670 align:middle line:84%
the enormous capacity, with
the emergence of our species,

01:22:00.670 --> 01:22:03.260 align:middle line:90%
for caring, for love.

01:22:03.260 --> 01:22:04.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

01:22:04.110 --> 01:22:07.450 align:middle line:84%
My goodness, you have given
us such a beautiful view

01:22:07.450 --> 01:22:10.600 align:middle line:84%
of how things definitely are
possible in the way-- you're

01:22:10.600 --> 01:22:11.170 align:middle line:90%
doing it.

01:22:11.170 --> 01:22:13.060 align:middle line:90%
You're shaping change.

01:22:13.060 --> 01:22:14.760 align:middle line:84%
You're such a
visionary in this way.

01:22:14.760 --> 01:22:16.790 align:middle line:84%
And I am so grateful
that you're here

01:22:16.790 --> 01:22:20.890 align:middle line:84%
to be able to explain how
applicable this is, how it's

01:22:20.890 --> 01:22:23.930 align:middle line:84%
just an action away
from happening,

01:22:23.930 --> 01:22:27.290 align:middle line:84%
that we, by understanding our
history, can change our future,

01:22:27.290 --> 01:22:29.480 align:middle line:84%
which we talked about
at the very beginning.

01:22:29.480 --> 01:22:32.480 align:middle line:84%
I want to just touch really
quickly on the working mother

01:22:32.480 --> 01:22:35.010 align:middle line:84%
concept we were talking
about before we watched that.

01:22:35.010 --> 01:22:38.870 align:middle line:84%
How do you think the
working mother has changed

01:22:38.870 --> 01:22:41.060 align:middle line:84%
the way that we're
raising children?

01:22:41.060 --> 01:22:43.910 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Well, you hear
a lot about how terrible

01:22:43.910 --> 01:22:46.050 align:middle line:84%
it is that women don't
stay home and take

01:22:46.050 --> 01:22:48.210 align:middle line:90%
care of their children.

01:22:48.210 --> 01:22:49.822 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I've heard that a lot.

01:22:49.822 --> 01:22:51.280 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: But that's
because people

01:22:51.280 --> 01:22:53.090 align:middle line:90%
don't know their history.

01:22:53.090 --> 01:22:55.200 align:middle line:84%
And they also don't
use their common sense.

01:22:55.200 --> 01:22:58.900 align:middle line:84%
If you look at the
old farm family,

01:22:58.900 --> 01:23:01.320 align:middle line:84%
that woman was not taking
care of her children.

01:23:01.320 --> 01:23:02.070 align:middle line:90%
It was usually--

01:23:02.070 --> 01:23:02.400 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: She was working.

01:23:02.400 --> 01:23:05.350 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: She was working on
the field, milking the cows,

01:23:05.350 --> 01:23:07.300 align:middle line:90%
cooking for the--

01:23:07.300 --> 01:23:08.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Tending the fields, yes.

01:23:08.930 --> 01:23:11.905 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: And it was usually the
oldest child, the oldest girl--

01:23:11.905 --> 01:23:12.780 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That raised--

01:23:12.780 --> 01:23:14.530 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --who took
care of the children.

01:23:14.530 --> 01:23:18.710 align:middle line:84%
And you still see that very much
in many parts of the developing

01:23:18.710 --> 01:23:19.880 align:middle line:90%
world today.

01:23:19.880 --> 01:23:22.807 align:middle line:84%
So that's a myth, the
way we never were, OK?

01:23:22.807 --> 01:23:23.640 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

01:23:23.640 --> 01:23:25.050 align:middle line:90%
I love that perspective, yes.

01:23:25.050 --> 01:23:26.940 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: All right,
so it isn't really

01:23:26.940 --> 01:23:29.370 align:middle line:90%
the quantity, anyway, of time.

01:23:29.370 --> 01:23:32.020 align:middle line:90%
It's the quality of time.

01:23:32.020 --> 01:23:34.890 align:middle line:84%
And it's also our understanding
of what good parenting is.

01:23:34.890 --> 01:23:40.100 align:middle line:84%
And we know now that this
fear and force based parenting

01:23:40.100 --> 01:23:42.110 align:middle line:90%
is not good parenting.

01:23:42.110 --> 01:23:44.620 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Right, but co-parenting
is a really good solution

01:23:44.620 --> 01:23:46.835 align:middle line:84%
to that, where both the men
and the women co-parent.

01:23:46.835 --> 01:23:47.710 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Absolutely.

01:23:47.710 --> 01:23:52.170 align:middle line:84%
And as I said, it's wonderful
that men now, as the gender

01:23:52.170 --> 01:23:54.280 align:middle line:84%
stereotypes are blurring,
as we're moving more

01:23:54.280 --> 01:23:57.480 align:middle line:84%
to the partnership
side, really don't

01:23:57.480 --> 01:24:00.890 align:middle line:84%
feel so threatened to
their status by going it.

01:24:00.890 --> 01:24:03.810 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And whereas it
comes to single mothers,

01:24:03.810 --> 01:24:05.420 align:middle line:84%
there's an economic
system that needs

01:24:05.420 --> 01:24:07.560 align:middle line:84%
to support single mothers
more by giving more

01:24:07.560 --> 01:24:09.294 align:middle line:84%
time for childcare
and more support.

01:24:09.294 --> 01:24:11.460 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Absolutely, but
it needs to also support--

01:24:11.460 --> 01:24:12.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Single fathers.

01:24:12.610 --> 01:24:14.880 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: --and
two parent couples.

01:24:14.880 --> 01:24:16.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

01:24:16.390 --> 01:24:20.520 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: That we are the only--
the only-- developed nation

01:24:20.520 --> 01:24:22.540 align:middle line:84%
that does not have
government supported

01:24:22.540 --> 01:24:27.850 align:middle line:84%
paid parental leave, that does
not invest in high quality

01:24:27.850 --> 01:24:30.590 align:middle line:84%
early childhood
education, that does not

01:24:30.590 --> 01:24:32.750 align:middle line:84%
have universal
childcare-- well, we

01:24:32.750 --> 01:24:35.350 align:middle line:84%
see it in the high
infant mortality rates.

01:24:35.350 --> 01:24:38.800 align:middle line:84%
We're the highest-- in
the highest poverty rates.

01:24:38.800 --> 01:24:41.190 align:middle line:90%
That's not being a superpower.

01:24:41.190 --> 01:24:46.450 align:middle line:84%
That is being really symptom of
a regression to the domination

01:24:46.450 --> 01:24:47.160 align:middle line:90%
side.

01:24:47.160 --> 01:24:52.160 align:middle line:84%
And we have to use the
current economic crisis,

01:24:52.160 --> 01:24:55.490 align:middle line:84%
where we can see that the
old system isn't working,

01:24:55.490 --> 01:25:00.227 align:middle line:84%
as an opportunity to
invest in-- just let's

01:25:00.227 --> 01:25:03.740 align:middle line:84%
put it in purely economic
terms-- in our human capital,

01:25:03.740 --> 01:25:08.690 align:middle line:84%
and give government support
for caring and care giving.

01:25:08.690 --> 01:25:12.560 align:middle line:84%
Because we're investing
in our competitiveness

01:25:12.560 --> 01:25:16.560 align:middle line:84%
as a nation in the
post-industrial knowledge

01:25:16.560 --> 01:25:18.350 align:middle line:90%
service economy.

01:25:18.350 --> 01:25:20.940 align:middle line:84%
That is a very
powerful argument.

01:25:20.940 --> 01:25:24.030 align:middle line:84%
I would like to see
the Occupy Movement

01:25:24.030 --> 01:25:27.360 align:middle line:84%
start talking about
a caring economy,

01:25:27.360 --> 01:25:29.970 align:middle line:84%
not just with what's
wrong, but what

01:25:29.970 --> 01:25:34.690 align:middle line:84%
can really, fundamentally
change the values.

01:25:34.690 --> 01:25:37.285 align:middle line:84%
Because economics is
about what we value.

01:25:37.285 --> 01:25:39.650 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And that is very
well put-- very well put.

01:25:39.650 --> 01:25:42.430 align:middle line:84%
And actually, you quote
Margaret Mead in this next clip.

01:25:42.430 --> 01:25:43.940 align:middle line:90%
She says it very well, as well.

01:25:43.940 --> 01:25:45.856 align:middle line:84%
Let's just take a look
at that really quickly.

01:25:45.856 --> 01:25:48.420 align:middle line:90%


01:25:48.420 --> 01:25:52.040 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: I want to close
by reminding us of something

01:25:52.040 --> 01:25:56.290 align:middle line:84%
that Margaret Mead pointed out,
that the only thing that ever

01:25:56.290 --> 01:26:01.900 align:middle line:84%
brought about positive change
is a group of dedicated women

01:26:01.900 --> 01:26:02.870 align:middle line:90%
and men.

01:26:02.870 --> 01:26:07.250 align:middle line:84%
So let's be that group of
dedicated women and men.

01:26:07.250 --> 01:26:12.630 align:middle line:84%
Let's join together to
really make that difference,

01:26:12.630 --> 01:26:18.290 align:middle line:84%
to send a steady stream of
pressure and information

01:26:18.290 --> 01:26:23.980 align:middle line:84%
and, yes, new thinking to our
policymakers, to our neighbors,

01:26:23.980 --> 01:26:28.200 align:middle line:84%
to our friends, to everyone
in our sphere of influence.

01:26:28.200 --> 01:26:31.900 align:middle line:84%
Let's do what we
need to do to move

01:26:31.900 --> 01:26:36.660 align:middle line:84%
to that economic system
that is so urgently needed

01:26:36.660 --> 01:26:41.330 align:middle line:84%
at this critical time in human
history, an economic system

01:26:41.330 --> 01:26:44.330 align:middle line:84%
that gives visibility
and value to the most

01:26:44.330 --> 01:26:48.010 align:middle line:84%
important human work, the
work of caring for people,

01:26:48.010 --> 01:26:52.350 align:middle line:84%
starting in childhood, and
caring for our Mother Earth.

01:26:52.350 --> 01:26:55.930 align:middle line:84%
So I invite you to
join me and the Center

01:26:55.930 --> 01:26:59.775 align:middle line:84%
for Partnership Studies in
this exciting and urgently

01:26:59.775 --> 01:27:01.610 align:middle line:90%
needed enterprise.

01:27:01.610 --> 01:27:02.760 align:middle line:90%
Let's do it.

01:27:02.760 --> 01:27:05.910 align:middle line:84%
Let's do it for ourselves,
for our children,

01:27:05.910 --> 01:27:08.220 align:middle line:90%
and for generations to come.

01:27:08.220 --> 01:27:09.350 align:middle line:90%
I thank you.

01:27:09.350 --> 01:27:10.940 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And let's
do it together.

01:27:10.940 --> 01:27:13.110 align:middle line:90%
Yes, I'm so inspired by that.

01:27:13.110 --> 01:27:16.770 align:middle line:84%
And I'm so inspired by
you, and motivated as well.

01:27:16.770 --> 01:27:20.040 align:middle line:84%
And you have opened
my mind to so many

01:27:20.040 --> 01:27:21.840 align:middle line:90%
wonderful possibilities.

01:27:21.840 --> 01:27:23.420 align:middle line:90%
I so appreciate you.

01:27:23.420 --> 01:27:24.170 align:middle line:90%
I really do.

01:27:24.170 --> 01:27:25.520 align:middle line:84%
>>EISLER: Oh, well
thank you my dear Lisa.

01:27:25.520 --> 01:27:26.519 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And I thank you.

01:27:26.519 --> 01:27:28.170 align:middle line:84%
I thank you for your
work, and for all

01:27:28.170 --> 01:27:30.711 align:middle line:84%
that you've given to us, and
the perspectives that you shared

01:27:30.711 --> 01:27:32.360 align:middle line:84%
with us this afternoon,
and everything

01:27:32.360 --> 01:27:36.200 align:middle line:84%
that you've done to move us
forward for social change.

01:27:36.200 --> 01:27:37.890 align:middle line:84%
You are really one
of the true pioneers.

01:27:37.890 --> 01:27:40.240 align:middle line:84%
But you're also one of
the ones making it happen.

01:27:40.240 --> 01:27:41.120 align:middle line:90%
So thank you.

01:27:41.120 --> 01:27:42.087 align:middle line:90%
Thank you so much.

01:27:42.087 --> 01:27:42.920 align:middle line:90%
>>EISLER: Thank you.

01:27:42.920 --> 01:27:43.950 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So wonderful.

